<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Congress on Immunology Opens in New Delhi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 1 (Xinhua) -- The global Congress on
Immunology opened here Sunday with a call by Indian President
Kocheril Raman Narayanan to free mankind from the scourge of
diseases.
</P>
<P>
Narayanan urged scientists of all countries in the world to
work together and share their knowledge and experience to achieve
this goal.
</P>
<P>
Over 2,600 scientists from 67 countries are attending the
week-long conference which is held once every three years.
</P>
<P>
Narayanan lamented that neither antibiotics nor the new
vaccines reach the poorest sections of the society who need them
most and asked scientists, industrialists and the governments to
"join hands so that fruits of research can be made available to
the common man with minimal delay at affordable cost".
</P>
<P>
This is the last global conference of immunologists in this
century and the millennium and also the first held in a developing
country.
</P>
<P>
The conference is organized by the International Union of
Immunological Societies with the Federation of Immunological
Societies of Asia and Oceania and the Indian Immunological Society
as sponsors.
</P>
<P>
The nine earlier meetings had been held in the developed world,
the last one at San Franciso of the United States in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing tenth conference will provide a forum for
discussions of the latest advances in immunology in six plenary
lectures, 25 symposia and 86 interactive workshops covering a wide
array of topics including the emerging technology of edible
vaccines for infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
Novel vaccines from plants, gene therapy, new methods for
control of AIDS and the latest research on allergic diseases like
asthma are among the topics to be discussed during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 500 distinguished scientists are scheduled to speak on
their fields of work in the symposia, workshops and the plenary
sessions, making it one of the greatest scientific events.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
