<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean, Namibian, Angolan Leaders Meet in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of Zimbabwe, Namibia
and Angola will hold a one-day summit Sunday in Lubumbashi of
Democratic Congo (DRC) to review the situation in the central
African country, the Zimbabwe News Agency Ziana reported.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, Namibian President Sam
Nujoma and Angolan President Eduardo dos Santos are expected to
attend the summit as they have now arrived in the second largest
city of Lubumbashi in southern Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
The three countries have deployed troops to assist Congolese
President Laurent Kabila in fighting a three-month rebellion led
by minority Congolese Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the meeting had been called by Nujoma to review a
hasty advance into eastern Congo where rebels claim control of a
third of the country and look set to fight on following collapsed
peace efforts recently in Lusaka, Ziana reported.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, together with the other allied forces has already
indicated that they will deploy more troops to help Kabila win
back the east especially the recently captured strategic town of
Kindu.
</P>
<P>
After the Lusaka talks on Congo (K), Mugabe has said the only
way toward bringing peace and stability to Congo is to intensify
the activities of the allied forces.
</P>
<P>
"The way forward is to continue to defend the DRC vigorously,
which we are doing, and knock sense into the minds of those who
are intransigent," Mugabe said, referring to Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Kabila and his three allies accuse Kigali of invading to back
the Congolese Rebels to occupy large tracts of territory in
eastern Congo, but Rwanda denies direct involvement.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe recently sent reinforcement of 2,000 troops to Congo
and it is now estimated to have more than 6,000 soldiers in Congo
(K). 
</P>
</TEXT>
