<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-01 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Calls for Battle Against Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At a special memorial service in the Knesset (Parliament),
Netanyahu said that there should be no room for violence of any
kind in Israel's political life.
</P>
<P>
He said it was no secret that he disagreed with the government
of Rabin over the Oslo peace accords, but stressed that both their
goals were to achieve lasting peace for Israel.
</P>
<P>
The most important thing, he emphasized, was that disputes
over political issues should be resolved without violence.
</P>
<P>
Peace must first be made between "brothers," Netanyahu said in
the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset memorial service was a part of nation-wide
activities to pay tribute to Rabin, who was murdered by a
rightist Jew in 1995, two years after he signed the historic Oslo
Accords with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
National flags were lowered to half mast in government
institutions and military bases. University students halted
demonstrations which have lasted for several days over tuition
fees, and a state memorial service was held at Mount Herzl, where
the slain prime minister lies in rest.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's appeal echoed his earlier remarks made in a weekly
cabinet meeting, in which he called on all political wings of
Israel to battle violence.
</P>
<P>
Many people note that since the assassination of Rabin three
years ago, the political atmosphere in Israel has not changed
much. The country is still widely divided, and the elements of
extremism still exist as demonstrated by recent wild incitement
campaigns against Netanyahu after he signed a land-for-peace deal
with Arafat last month.
</P>
<P>
Recent polls have showed that more than 60 percent of the
Israelis believe that no lessons have been learnt from the
tragedy of Rabin, and almost half of the Israelis said there is a
high chance for another political assassination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
