<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-01 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Urged to Halt Settlement Activity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian chief negotiator
Saeb Erekat on Sunday urged Israel to halt housing construction in
Ras Al-Amud in East Jerusalem and give peace a chance.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Israeli Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh, Erekat
said the attempt to start housing construction in Ras Al-Amud by a
group of Jewish people is a blatant violation to the signed peace
agreements which prohibit unilateral measures.
</P>
<P>
Erekat called for immediate measures by the Israeli government
to stop the settlement activities in Ras Al-Amud, reported
Jerusalem Media and Communication Center, a Palestinian media
center based in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, a group of Jewish people tried to start housing
construction in Ras Al-Amud, a Palestinian Arab quarter in East
Jerusalem. Their activities were stopped by Jerusalem police amid
protests by representatives of Israel's peace group Peace Now and
other Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
Conflicts also erupted on Sunday at the scene when a number of
Peace Now members tried to move away the fence set up days ago by
a group of Israeli Knesset (parliament) right-wing members. As a
result, three Peace Now members were arrested by police.
</P>
<P>
Israel's Prime Minister's Office said Sunday that although
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu did not issue his permit for
housing construction in Ras Al-Amud, the fence placed there is
legal and nobody is allowed to move them.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side has strongly opposed such a move, stating
East Jerusalem is part of the occupied territory and the Israeli
side has no right to build any house there.
</P>
<P>
Some four months ago, Israel's Jerusalem municipality issued
permits to build 132 departments for Jewish housing on an empty
plot in Ras Al-Amud, which is said to be owned by American
millionaire Irving Moskowitz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
