<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-01 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Warns Against Connecting Cyprus Problem to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister
Ioannis Kasoulides has warned that any effort to associate a
settlement to the Cyprus problem with the republic's European
Union (EU) accession course would make a Cyprus solution
impossible.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides made the remarks Sunday at Larnaca Airport prior to
his departure for Athens, the first stop in his tour of European
countries to discuss Cyprus' efforts to join the EU and
developments in the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on efforts by some EU member states to associate
the Cyprus question to its EU course, Kasoulides said that "any
connection of the Cyprus problem to the accession course will
signal the end of efforts to settle the Cyprus issue."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved despite the
international community's peace efforts in the past 24 years.
</P>
<P>
"If the Cyprus problem and the EU accession course are
officially associated, this would constitute an invitation to
Turkey not to allow a settlement," Kasoulides explained.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister added that in the meantime, such a stance
would not facilitate EU efforts to bring Turkey closer to Europe.
</P>
<P>
"As the EU itself has stated, the Cyprus issue is one of the
important obstacles in forging closer ties with Turkey," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus submitted its application for EU membership in 1990. The
EU started accession talks with Cyprus in March this year.
</P>
<P>
On his scheduled meeting in the Greek capital of Athens with
Greek Foreign Ministry officials, Kasoulides said it is to be held
within the framework of regular contacts between the two
governments.
</P>
<P>
He said that he will discuss "the situation in the Cyprus
problem and Cyprus' EU accession course" with Greek officials.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting in Athens, Kasoulides will visit Spain and
Britain. On November 8, he will fly to Brussels where he will
represent the Cypriot government in the start of substantive
accession talks with the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
