<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CBI Survey Highlights Risk of Taking UK into </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BIRMINGHAM, November 1 (Xinhua) - Many British companies are
more confident about their own prospects than they are about the
UK economy as a whole, according to a survey of economic
conditions carried out by the Confederation of British Industry
(CBI).
</P>
<P>
The overwhelming majority also believe the Monetary Policy
Committee (MPC) should cut rates on Thursday, with over half
wanting a cut of 0.5 percent, the CBI said.
</P>
<P>
The survey, released at the CBI's National Conference here
Sunday afternoon, covers macro-economic conditions and business
attitudes to recent labor market legislation.
</P>
<P>
When asked if they were more optimistic or pessimistic for
their own businesses in 1999 as compared with 1998, 19 percent
said they were more optimistic while 47 percent said they were
more pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
And at least a quarter of firms indicate that they plan to
increase their number of employees, and their levels of
investment, next year.
</P>
<P>
But when asked the same question for the UK as a whole, only
two percent said they were optimistic, while 83 percent thought
the UK economy would perform worse next year.
</P>
<P>
Introducing the results, Adair Turner, CBI Director-General,
said: "The fact that so many more firms are concerned about the
overall economy than for their own prospects highlights the danger
of talking too much about recession."
</P>
<P>
"Many people clearly believe things will get worse but not for
them - perhaps because they are alarmed by media hype about global
meltdown," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Turner admitted: "This is clearly a very difficult
time for some key sectors and we do expect a sharp economic
slowdown." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
