<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Government Must Avoid Burdening Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BIRMINGHAM, November 1 (Xinhua) - Tax and administrative
burdens on companies have risen over the past year and are hurting
business competitiveness at a time when the economy is facing a
downturn, according to the Confederation of British Industry
(CBI).
</P>
<P>
Chancellor Gordon Brown must not add to them in his next budget
and where possible should look to cut business taxes to promote
innovation and entrepreneurship, it argues.
</P>
<P>
In its recommendations to the Chancellor in advance of the
Pre-Budget Report on Tuesday, the CBI states that taxes on
business have been pushed up by over 5 billion pounds a year
during 1997/8 - 2001/01, due to the part two budgets, and by over
8 billion pounds a year as a result of successive budgets since
1993.
</P>
<P>
Added to this the cost of complying with tax and other business
regulations increasingly a major cause of concern, the CBI adds.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the start of the CBI's National Conference Sunday
afternoon, Clive Thompson, CBI President, said: "There is a real
danger that the burden of all this tax and regulation will move
business further away from its real business - wealth creation."
</P>
<P>
"The sheer volume of tax - 20 billion pounds over the next four
years - and the administrative burden created by complex tax
proposals, are adding both to uncertainty and workloads," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Another senior official from the CBI also said: "It is essential
that no additional tax or administrative burdens are placed on
business if we are to avoid a further reduction in our
effectiveness." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
