<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Public Finances Underpin Spending Plans for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BIRMINGHAM, November 1 (Xinhua) - The Government's
Comprehensive Spending Review plans are not under threat from
short term economic pressures, according to the Confederation of
British Industry (CBI).
</P>
<P>
But there is still the challenge of developing a long-term
strategy for coping with rising demands on key public services, it
adds.
</P>
<P>
The CBI believes the UK public finances are in a fundamentally
sound condition, following five years of sustained fiscal
consolidation. The public/debt GDP ratio is at a reasonable
sustainable level, and the public deficit close to balance.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the CBI's National Conference here Sunday
afternoon, Kate Barker, Chief Economic Advisor, said: "This sound
position is not put at risk by the public spending increase
announced for the next three years."
</P>
<P>
However, she stressed: "The Government must ensure that value
for money is obtained for the extra spending granted to
departments."
</P>
<P>
The principal concern is the longer-term trend. Public spending
as a percentage of GDP is set to rise and it is essential that
this trend does not go any further, with pressure for improved
health and education likely to continue, said, Kate Barker.
</P>
<P>
"Of more concern is the need for the Government to demonstrate
it will 'think the unthinkable' in order to contain long term
public finances," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
