<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair: It Is Time to Improve British-German Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 1 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
has declared that London would grasp the opportunity of the recent
power change in Bonn to foster new political relations between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
In an article contributed to the German Sunday newspaper Welt
am Sonntag ahead of a visit to London by Germany's new chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder, Blair noted that Germany, not the Commonwealth
or the United States, was now the most important trading partner
of Britain.
</P>
<P>
"The politics follows the trade... Therefore I believe that it
is time to change the political relations between our two
countries in order to match it with the increasingly closer
economic relations as well as personal contacts," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the similarity between the policies pursued Germany's
new Social Democratic government under Schroeder and his Labour
government, Blair said that what Schroeder called "the New Center"
and what he called "the Third Way" was "a modernized Social
Democracy which combines efficiency and entrepreneurship with
social justice and fairness".
</P>
<P>
"With the election of Schroeder a new generation has taken over
power in a new center-left Europe," Blair declared.
</P>
<P>
Taking care not to arouse fears from Paris, Blair stressed that
Britain was determined to be a leading partner in Europe, but
would not in the meantime threaten the relations between Germany
and France.
</P>
<P>
"We want to enrich the European Union (EU) and show what
contributions can be made by a Britain that oriented itself
positively towards Europe," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder, who just took office last week to replace the
conservative government under the veteran chancellor Helmut Kohl,
will meet Blair on Monday on his first official visit to Britain
as German chancellor.
</P>
<P>
According to Blair, he and Schroeder would discuss how London
and Bonn could better cooperate on European issues such as
fighting unemployment, EU reforms and its eastward enlargement.
</P>
<P>
They would also discuss how Europe could play a bigger role in
international affairs, Blair said.
</P>
<P>
"The NATO should remain as the foundation of the collective
security in Europe. But in the meanwhile, Europe, as a supplement
to the alliance, should be in a position to act credibly under its
own initiative even at times when the United States do not support
us," the British leader said in the article. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
