<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Ready to Resume Talks With Israel: Mubarak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
said Sunday that Syria is willing to resume talks with Israel by
picking up from where they left off.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after meeting with visiting Syrian
President Hafez al-Assad, Mubarak blamed Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu for rejecting Syria's offer.
</P>
<P>
He called on Netanyahu to "create the right atmosphere for
confidence-building" in a bid to dispel Syria's distrust of his
Likud government.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli talks came to a halt in early 1996 due to
disputes over the future of the Golan Heights captured by Israel
from Syria in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
Syria argued that the former Israeli Labor government has
agreed to a pullback from the Golan Heights and that the
negotiations should be resumed from that point. But Netanyahu
insists that the talks start from zero.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak also urged Syria and Turkey to continue solving
disputes through negotiations now that they have settled some of
the problems.
</P>
<P>
Ankara threatened military actions last month to stop what it
denounced as Damascus' support for the Kurdish rebels seeking an
independent state in the southeast of Turkey, sparking fears of a
regional conflict.
</P>
<P>
Mediated by Egypt and Iran, Syria agreed on October 20 to stop
sheltering the Kurdish rebels and not to allow cross-border
attacks on Turkey by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
On the recent interim peace accord between the Palestinians and
Israelis, Mubarak said that Egypt has no objection to the deal as
long as the Palestinians have accepted it. He called for full
implementation of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Netanyahu signed the
agreement on October 23 in Washington on Israeli further pullback
from the West Bank and the Palestinians' crackdown on Islamic
extremists.
</P>
<P>
Al-Assad arrived in the Egyptian Red Sea resort Sharm el Sheikh
in the day for a regular coordination of stances on regional
issues with Mubarak. He left for home after the summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
