<HEADLINE> 28 Brotherhood Members Detained in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Egypt ordered Sunday the remand
of 28 members of the outlawed Muslim Brotherhood for 15 days
pending investigations, Egypt's Middle East News Agency (MENA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
The arrestees will face charges of association with an illegal
group, possession of written materials against the state and
inciting anti-government demonstrations, MENA said.
</P>
<P>
They were also accused of trying to revive activities of a
banned organization and reshape its secret structures in several
governorates.
</P>
<P>
The defendants include a physician, a pharmacist, two civil
engineers and an unemployed university graduate.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim Brotherhood, Egypt's largest Islamic fundamentalist
group, was banned in the 1950s, but was tolerated until 1995 when
the government began to crack down on it.
</P>
<P>
The group advocates an Islamic state in Egypt, but says it does
not believe violence is the way to bring that about. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
