<HEADLINE> South African Vice President Visits Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Executive Vice President of
South African Thabo Mbeki arrived in Riyadh on Sunday on an
official visit aimed at enhancing bilateral economic cooperation,
the Kuwaiti News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The South African diplomats in Riyadh said Mbeki, also
president of the ruling African National Congress of South Africa,
will hold talks with Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz and other
senior Saudi officials mainly on means of boosting economic, trade
and investment cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also discuss ways of strengthening
political coordination on regional and international issues of
mutual concern, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi and South African officials will review the
situation in the Gulf region after the latest Iraqi decision to
suspend cooperation with U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in
charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, said the
sources.
</P>
<P>
Iraq on Saturday announced that it has decided to suspend all
its relations with UNSCOM until the commission has been
restructured and its chairman Richard Butler has been removed.
</P>
<P>
Developments of the Middle East peace process will also be
among the topics to be discussed, the diplomatic sources added.
</P>
<P>
This is the second visit by Mbeki to Saudi Arabia in less than
two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
