<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Since the beginning of Egypt's cotton exporting season
this year a few weeks ago, the number of export contracts has
increased by 15 percent than that in the whole exporting season
last year, Egyptian daily "Al Akhbar" reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
So far, export contracts have committed more than 1.3 million
Kantars (58.5 million kilograms) of cotton and 11 percent of the
amount has been transported to the foreign market.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The French company ALCATEL has won a contract to
expand telephone lines in a number of Yemeni governorates,
Sunday's "Al Hayat" newspaper quoted an official of the Yemeni
Ministry of Communications as saying.
</P>
<P>
The official pointed out that the project entails the addition
of 59,472 new lines at a total cost of approximately 29 million
French Francs (about 5.2 million U.S. dollars)
</P>
<P>
A report issued by the Telecommunications Authority indicates
that the cost of other projects currently being implemented in 70
different locations will run to some 87 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report anticipates that the new telephone projects will add
about 134,000 new lines, bringing the total telephone lines in
Yemen to 412,000 lines.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- An Arab Economic Exhibition will be held in Beirut
from November 5 to 12. Syria, Egypt, Lebanon and other Arab states
will participate in the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will host industrialists, artisans, exporters
and importers from the Arab world. They will all exhibit their
products, establish inter-Arab contacts and promote trade
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran and South Korea on Saturday signed a letter of
understanding to improve their trade exchanges, especially in the
area of the small and medium-sized industries, the official news
agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The letter was signed by Secretary of Iran's Chamber of
Commerce whose name was only given as Govahi, and visiting
Chairman of Iran-Korea Economic Cooperation Committee Han Dik.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official said the value of annual trade exchanges
between Iran and South Korea is about 2 billion U.S. dollars, of
which 1.4 billion dollars is Iran's exports to South Korea,
including 180 million dollars non-oil products such as
agro-products, textiles, and minerals.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Minister of Mines and Metals Eshaq Jahangiri
said on Saturday that the country has so far earned 375 million
U.S. dollars from exports of metal products this year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the official news agency IRNA in the southwestern
province of Chahamal-Bakhtiari, Jahangiri said that metal exports
would fetch 500 million dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
He expressed regret that although Iran is the second producer
of mineral and dimensional stones worldwide, it has the least
share in export of such goods in the world market.
</P>
<P>
The average volume of mineral stones' export stands at 38
million dollars annually, the minister said, adding that there
are 2,008 active mines in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
