<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Urged to Be Involved in Pak-India Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Chairman of the
Senate Wasim Sajjad Monday urged a close involvement of the
European Union in the Pak-India dialogue process to bring about a
lasting and durable peace in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the first Pak-German dialogue at the Institute of
Strategic Studies (ISS) here, Wasim said that Pakistan, with all
sincerity of purpose, has resumed the dialogue process with India
for the resolution of all outstanding problems including the core
issue of Kashmir, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
The Kashmir issue has been bedeviling bilateral relations
between the two countries as well as vitiating environment of
peace and security in South Asia, Wasim said.
</P>
<P>
"If only India could be persuaded by third parties to show a
flexible and innovative attitude on the core issue, I have no
doubt that we can then move easily to expand ties in other fields
as well," said the chairman.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to emphasize our resolve for peace and security
in the nuclearized South Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that "we appreciate the understanding of the
European Union towards the compulsions which led to our nuclear
tests and growing realization of an urgent need for an early
resolution of the Kashmir issue."
</P>
<P>
The three-day Pak-German dialogue has been jointly organized by
ISS, Hans Seidel Foundation, Munich, and the Research Institute
for International Studies, Munich. 
</P>
</TEXT>
