<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians Oppose Trafficking in Personal Information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Nine in 10 Canadians strongly
disapprove of companies traficking in information about their
private lives, according to a survey published Monday.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether it is acceptable for companies to sell,
trade or share detailed lists of personal information to other
organizations, 23 percent respondents said it is "not very
acceptable" and 65 percent said it is "not at all acceptable."
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that 80 percent of the respondents think
personal data should be kept strictly confidential, unless the
information is needed for medical emergencies or to enforce the
law.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted between July 15 and 21 by polling firm
Angus Reid Group, has a margin of error of plus or minus 2.5
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
At present, there is no law in Canada that ensures consumer
privacy and regulates how information about consumers is collected
and used in private sector, according to the Globe and Mail
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the government proposed a federal privacy bill that
outlines how organizations should deal with personal consumer
information.
</P>
<P>
The bill is expected to be fast-tracked through the system as
concerns about electronic privacy continues to mount, the paper
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
