<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Approves Draft National Water Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's National Water
Resources Council (NWRC) Monday approved the country's first ever
draft national water policy which envisages appropriate use of
water without jeopardizing the interest of any member of society,
the official BSS news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The approval was given at NWRC's 4th meeting held with Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina in the chair.
</P>
<P>
As a riverine country the importance of water resource is
immense in the national life, Hasina said. "Water is resource for
us and at the same time a cause of sorrow and grief also," she
said, adding that through proper harnessing, storage and
utilization, "we have to ensure the best and optimum use of these
precious resources."
</P>
<P>
She particularly underlined the importance of protecting the
natural water reservoirs so that the local condition and
environment are not disturbed.
</P>
<P>
The draft policy was totally enunciated by the local water
resource persons and water experts without any help from foreign
consultants, Water Resources Minister Abdur Razzak said while
presenting the policy.
</P>
<P>
The policy, which will act as a future guideline for proper
water management, incorporates all aspects of availability,
storage and utilization of rain water, surface water and ground
water and their sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
Besides, it has also laid emphasis on both public and private
actions for ensuring optimal development of water resources that
benefits both individual and society at large, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The main objectives of the policy are to redress issues related
to the harnessing and development of all forms of surface water
and ground water and management of these resources in an efficient
and equitable manner and ensure the availability of water to all
sections of society.
</P>
<P>
The highlights of the policy are: to develop a state of
knowledge and capability that will enable the country to design
future water resources management plans by itself with economic
efficiency, gender equality, social, justice and environmental
awareness and to facilitate achievement of the water management
objectives through broad public participation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
