<HEADLINE> Wushu Apply to IOC for Recognition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The International Wushu
Federation (IWUF), the world governing body for the Chinese
martial art sport known as Wushu, applied Monday to International
Olympic Committee (IOC) for recognition of the sport here.
</P>
<P>
In the letter direct to IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch,
IWUF president Wu Shaozu said, "I have great pleasure in formally
applying to you for recognition in the name of the sport of
Wushu."
</P>
<P>
The original applying letter have been sent to the
headquarters of IOC and duplicate one was handed to IOC executive
commissioner He Zhenliang Monday. He said the application will
be discussed in an IOC executive committee meeting next month.
</P>
<P>
But He said the recognition of the sport of Wushu does not
mean it could be listed as an official event into the Olympic
Games.
</P>
<P>
"It's easy to get recognised, but to join the Olympic Games is
not so easy."
</P>
<P>
A total of 34 sports will feature in the 2000 Olympic Games
while the other 27 items are eager to join the Olympics spree.
</P>
<P>
IWUF has held four World Championships and four Congresses
since it was established on October 3, 1990. It has 77 member
associations from throughout the world. 
</P>
