<HEADLINE> Zambian Police Shoot Rioting Youth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambian police Monday morning
shot dead a youth in Luansha, a mining town about 360 kilometers
north of Lusaka, to squelch a rioting over miners' salaries and
housing allowance.
</P>
<P>
This was the first death recorded since the rioting began last
Tuesday at Roan Antelope Mining Corporation of Zambia (RAMCZ)
based in Luansha.
</P>
<P>
The boy was shot by police at the back of his head and the
brain was splashed on the spot in the city centre, the Zambia
News Agency ZANA reported.
</P>
<P>
Most of the youths from the mine township had a running battle
Monday morning with the police and shifted the war from the
townships to the town center.
</P>
<P>
The strike at the mining company entered its six day with the
miners vowing that they would not resume work until their demands
to get their September salaries, 25 percent housing allowance and
to remove their land rates being charged by the mines, are met.
</P>
<P>
The tense situation in Luansha resulted in shop owners closing
their shops for fear of looting and parents going to schools to
fetch their children.
</P>
<P>
By 11:00 hours (local time), the town was abandoned and only
police vehicles were patrolling the area, said ZANA.
</P>
<P>
In the past days, hundreds of miners accompanied by their
wives and children have looted the mine police office, destroyed
a number of clubs and smashed several vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Management at RAMCZ Sunday resolved with the union officials
that the miners get back to work and be paid their salaries, but
the uncompromising workers refused to budge.
</P>
<P>
In a response to the strike, Zambian Deputy Minister of Mines,
Kaunda Lembalemba, threatened Sunday that the government would be
forced to intervene in the wrangling at the mining company if the
union and the management could not resolve their dispute within
48 hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
