<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's foreign currency reserves rose 129
million U.S. dollars in October to 21.94 billion dollars, the
Bank of Israel said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The foreign currency market was very active in October as the
shekel depreciated 10.5 percent against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's internal revenues will this year show an
8 billion shekels (1.84 billion U.S. dollars) shortfall "at the
very least," officials from the Finance Ministry said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, some 4.7 billion shekels (1.08 billion dollars) is
offset by a reduction in government expenditure in the wake of
the economic slowdown, while the remainder is principally the
result of a lack of activity in the construction industry and a
substantial fall in the number of vehicle imports.
</P>
<P>
JEDDA -- Well-informed sources anticipate that the four
principal electricity companies in Saudi Arabia will merge,
together with other companies and the General Electricity
Authority, into one holding company under the name of "Saudi
Arabian Electricity Company" before 1999.
</P>
<P>
The four principal companies are the "Central," the "Western,"
the "Eastern" and the "Southern" companies.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- The World Bank has granted Yemen 14 million dollars
in subsidy to finance part of the projected restoration of the old
city at Fez which the UNESCO classifies as world human heritage,
its history dating back to the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
A World Bank official told the Arabic newspaper Al Hayat in an
interview published Monday that a similar subsidy will go to the
old city at Soweira overlooking the Atlantic Ocean to preverve its
heritage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
