<HEADLINE> Leading Auction House Enjoys Successful Autumn Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Successful autumn sales
completed last week by China's largest auction house indicate that
the collectibles market weathered the adverse effects of the
worldwide economic slump.
</P>
<P>
Guardian auctioneers sold items valued at 66.65 million yuan
(eight million U.S. dollars) during a three-day auction over the
weekend. The volume was the company's third largest in history.
</P>
<P>
"We anticipated sluggish sales and never imagined the auction
would be so successful," according to Kou Qin, vice-president of
China Guardian Auctions.
</P>
<P>
Auctioneers sold paintings by Chen Yifei, Ding Shaoguang and Wu
Guanzhong at good prices, with an oil landscape by Liao Chi-Chun,
a well-known painter in Taiwan, selling for 1.21 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
A Landscape Painting by Qi Baishi, a master of traditional
Chinese painting, sold for a record 1.595 million yuan. One work
by Xu Beihong sold for 1.32 million, with a second work bringing
in 1.1 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
An ancient Yuan Dynasty (1271-1368) painting and Chinese
calligraphy written by the Emperor Qianlong of the Qing Dynasty
(1644-1911), attracted great interest and led to spirited
bidding. The pieces finally reached 1.21 million yuan and 935,000
yuan respectively.
</P>
<P>
An eight-volume of rare books formerly housed in the well-known
ancient Danshengtang Library, but missing for hundreds of years,
sold for 220,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Most other items on the block, including a treasured sapphire,
gold coins and chinaware, sold well beyond minimum prices set by
the auctioneers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
