<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Funds Promote Balanced Fertilization Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Balanced Fertilization
Project funded by the United Nations Development Program (UNDP)
has helped targeted areas in China increase grain output by 2.42
million tons and raise farmers' total income by 1.52 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The project, initiated in 1992, has been carried out on 600,000
hectares of farmland in seven provinces, according to an
international balanced fertilization seminar which opened today in
the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in targeted areas are paying greater attention to the
scientific and efficient use of fertilizers. Statistics for 1997
show that the fertilizers use rate in the areas stood at 37.3
percent, up 8.2 percentage points on the 1992 level, equivalent to
increasing the use of fertilizers by 28.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The project has also provided valuable experience for spreading
technology. In 1995, the Ministry of Agriculture listed balanced
fertilization program as one of 10 key technology projects for
introduction nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Balanced fertilization has been introduced to over 20 million
hectares of farmland nationwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agriculture Minister Chen Meets Belgian Counterpart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Minister of Agriculture
Chen Yaobang met here today with the Belgian Minister of Agriculture
and Small- and Medium-Sized Enterprises, Karel Pinxten.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed that the European Union (EU) should
consider unique conditions in China when importing Chinese
agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
Chen also mentioned the EU ban on imports of poultry, meat and
marine products from China due to sanitation problems.
</P>
<P>
He said the EU should fully consider the fact that China is a
vast country with quite different conditions in various regions.
</P>
<P>
Pinxten expressed his understanding of the views. He pointed
out that the EU is also a big region and noted that many nations
find hard to operate under a single standard.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that Belgium will help keep the lines of
communications between China and the EU open, so long as Chinese
districts follow EU sanitation regulations.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that the EU ban on China's marine products will
be lifted by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also discussed bilateral exchanges related to
agricultural science and technology.
</P>
<P>
China, a large agricultural country in need of more
agricultural production technology, hopes to learn from Belgium's
advanced expertise in the field, said Chen.
</P>
<P>
Pinxten said Belgium hopes to enhance communications with
China in related areas.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders briefly discussed cooperation between the two
countries' small- and medium-sized enterprises, and China's
membership in the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Pinxten is visiting China as part of a delegation led by Prime
Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene. 
</P>
</TEXT>
