<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guinea Bissau Peace Deal Signed in Abuja </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Opposing sides in Guinea
Bissau's five-month civil war have signed an agreement to end the
conflict in the West African country, official source in Abuja
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The peace deal was signed late Sunday night after talks in the
Nigerian capital between Guinea Bissau President Joao Bernardo
Vieira and the rebel leader Ansumane Mane.
</P>
<P>
The agreement calls for both parties to adhere to the
cease-fire signed in August, withdraw all foreign forces and
introduce a West African peace-keeping force.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, a government of national unity will be formed
within 10 days and presidential elections will be held no later
than March 1999.
</P>
<P>
Talks between the two sides started Thursday in Gambian
capital Banjul and restarted in Abuja where President Vieira was
attending the 21st Summit of the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) from October 30-31.
</P>
<P>
The talks were brokered by Gambian President Yaya Jammeh.
</P>
<P>
Mane, former Chief of Army Staff, led a rebel against Vieira
in June after he was sacked for involvement of army officers in
arms smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Neighboring Senegal and Guinea sent troops to Vieira's aid,
but the rebel forces gained control over most of the country.
</P>
<P>
The conflicts have resulted in the displacement of about half
of Guinea Bissau's one million population.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
