<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Anticipates New Securities Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The widely anticipanted first
securities law is expected to win the approval of China's highest
legislative body within this year, according to a renowned Chinese
economist.
</P>
<P>
Li Yining, a member of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress (NPC), participated in drafting the law and
pointed out that members of the NPC Standing Committee reached a
consensus on major issues following heated rounds of serious
debates and discussions. Li made the comments during a Monday
interview with the Xinhua News Agency and added the legislature
will quite likely pass the law during its December session.
</P>
<P>
He pointed to the securities market as an indispensable part of
China's socialist market economy, and noted that timely
promulgation of the law is needed to ensure the healthy
development of both the economy and market itself.
</P>
<P>
The first draft of the law was submitted to the NPC Standing
Committee for deliberation in 1993 and had simply been tabled for
four years prior to this year's current committee session.
</P>
<P>
Li, who also serves as deputy director of the NPC's Economic
and Financial Committee, stressed that differences of opinion
largely center on issues concerning the securities management
system, the range and scope of the law, spot and futures
transactions, and business lineages of securities companies.
</P>
<P>
Most legislators agree that the securities management system
should be subject to the dual leadership of the central and local
governments.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that the draft fails to cover futures trading.
However, according to Li, "that is in no way tantamount to a ban
on futures trading."
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the draft law is far from perfect since the
securities market is highly complicated, and it is extremely
difficult to establish concrete guidelines for various activities
such as off-market trading and the approval system for companies
intending to float shares.
</P>
<P>
China's securities law should eventually be in line with the
laws of other countries, "but the proper conditions do not as yet
exist," said Li.
</P>
<P>
He warned that bad debts held by banks, the decline in the
quality of listed companies and illegal fund-raising activities
are posing grave challenges to the country's young securities
market.
</P>
<P>
"The Securities Law will, at least to some extent, help reduce
market risk, but will in no way solve all existing problems," said
Li. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
