<HEADLINE> Israeli Speaker Proposes to Cancel Rabin's Memorial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Knesset (Parliament)
Speaker Dan Tichon on Monday asked lawmakers to agree to cancel
the Knesset special memorial session for late Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin next year.
</P>
<P>
Tichon said in his proposal that Rabin's assassination has to
be remembered, but it was sad that the Knesset special session for
Rabin has been turned into a gathering of mutual attacks among
political parties.
</P>
<P>
Rabin, who inked the Oslo accords with the Palestinians, was
assassinated on November 4, 1995 in Tel Aviv by a right-wing
extremist opposed to the peace process. Various memorial
ceremonies were held across the country each year.
</P>
<P>
"The Knesset is a place for promoting democracy and a forum for
members from different parties to voice their concerns and views
which could be conducive to national interests and unity, but what
happened during Sunday's special session for Rabin deepened the
rift between the parties," Tichon was reported as saying.
</P>
<P>
During Sunday's Knesset session for Rabin, political party
leaders tried to send a message of unity, but their words were
drowned by their political division.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the session, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu from
the right-wing Likud urged for national unity, but said that he
did not agree with Rabin on the Oslo accords, the cornerstone of
the Israeli-Palestinian peace making.
</P>
<P>
Labor Party leader Ehud Barak said the first lesson that
should be learned about Rabin's assassination is that "words can
kill," referring to what was called Netanyahu's anti-Rabin
incitement before the murder took place.
</P>
<P>
Meretz leader Yossi Darid delivered an emotional speech, in
which he accused the Netanyahu government of rejecting the Oslo
accords.
</P>
<P>
Leah Rabin, widow of the late prime minister, refused to have
any reconciliation with Netanyahu because the right-wingers are
still smearing Rabin for what they called the "terrible Oslo
accords." 
</P>
</TEXT>
