<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fresh Water Crisis Looming in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The swelling population in
Nigeria has forced the increase in water supply as water
availability is projected to shrink by more than half within the
next three decades, The Guardian newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Water supply in Nigeria is predicted to drop from 2,506 cubic
meters per year each person three years ago to 1,175 cubic meters
by the year 2025, when the population is estimated to increase
from 111.7 million in 1995 to 238.4 million.
</P>
<P>
The fresh water shortage in Nigeria is mainly caused by the
shrinkage of water supply in Lake Chad which is one of the
major fresh water sources in the West African country, according
to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Studies now confirm that Lake Chad on Nigeria's northeastern
tip has shrunk from a surface area of 25,000 square kilometers to
just 2,000 square kilometers due to over-use and drought over the
last three decades.
</P>
<P>
An international study conducted by the U.S.-based John
Kopkins University this year ranked Nigeria among countries which
could run out of water within the next three decades.
</P>
<P>
By 1995, the study said, some 31 countries with a combined
population of more than 458 million people were facing some
measure of water crisis.
</P>
<P>
The study noted that the number of people facing water crisis
is expected to swell to about 2.8 billion people spreading over
48 countries or up to one third of projected world population.
</P>
<P>
Three key factors are mainly blamed for the shrinking water
sources, namely, the swelling population, increased demand by
substantial growth in industrial, agricultural activities and
mass urbanization, and widespread of population of available
water resources, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Expose Three Major Tax Evasion Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The State General
Administration of Taxation announced today that it will release
details of three major tax evasion cases to the media in the near
future as part nationwide crackdown on tax evasions and frauds.
</P>
<P>
The three cases -- Jinhua, Enwei and Nangong -- occurred in
Zhejiang, Sichuan and Hebei provinces respectively.
</P>
<P>
The administration will publicize the names of delinquent
taxpayers on a regular basis, and will instruct local taxation
departments to establish a system for publicizing tax evasion
cases.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the system will be to enhance awareness of the need
to conscientiously pay taxes and eliminate the idea that "owing
taxes is both reasonable and beneficial," according to one
administration official.
</P>
<P>
The administration also plans to spend the next two months in
an intensified effort to achieve this year's target for increasing
industrial and commercial tax revenues to 100 billion yuan (about
12 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Various measures thus far adopted include inspections of tax
collection procedure in key industries such as the tobacco, power
and petroleum sectors, as well as in private and overseas-funded
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The administration also plans to closely monitor financial
departments to ensure the timely payment of taxes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
