<HEADLINE> China Gradually Opens Financial Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- China will continue to deepen
financial system reform and open its financial market in a
step-by-step manner, according to Dai Xianglong, governor of the
People's Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
Dai made the remarks today during a meeting with Belgian Prime
Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene.
</P>
<P>
He said China will continue to carry out the policy of opening
its financial sector, and pointed to the fact that the country has
approved branches for nine foreign banks and four foreign
insurance companies since the Asian financial crisis erupted in
July last year.
</P>
<P>
He added that foreign banks are allowed to conduct Chinese
currency transactions in Shanghai and Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
Dai said it is imperative to improve the central bank's
supervisory capacity, financial regulations and the overall
quality of Chinese financial professionals. Therefore, the
process of opening China's financial sector will be proceeded in
accordance with the step-by-step principle, according to Dai.
</P>
<P>
Dehaene said the Belgian financial sectors is fully prepared to
cooperate with Chinese partners. He also pointed out that the
stability of the Chinese currency (yuan) continues to play an
important role in stabilizing the Asian financial situation.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also exchanged views on other issues of common
concern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
