<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Egyptian Antiquities First Presented in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 2 (Xinhua) -- An Asian premiere exhibition
on Egyptian culture and antiquities will be staged in Hong Kong
starting Tuesday, for the city dwellers to catch a glimpse of the
brilliant civilization the nation achieved some 5,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Entitled "Egyptian Treasures from the British Museum," the
exhibition was jointly opened Monday by the Provisional Urban
Council's Chairman Ronald Leung Ding-bong, British Consul-General
Andrew Burns and Director of Urban Services Elaine Chung Lai-kwok.
</P>
<P>
In his speech Leung recalled that "National Treasures - Gems of
China's Cultural Relics" exhibition presented last year by the
council had won enthusiastic support from Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
"This year, we present the 'Egyptian Treasures' and I very much
hope that our viewers will respond with a similar degree of
admiration, since China and Egypt are both great civilizations
with thousands of years' history," he said.
</P>
<P>
One hundred and five items of ancient Egyptian treasures,
covering the period from 3,000 B.C. to 300 B.C., are all specially
selected from the British Museum which houses one of the greatest
collections of Egyptian antiquities in the world.
</P>
<P>
One of the star items of the exhibition is a decorated coffin
with a wrapped mummy inside. Stupendous mummy masks are also
featured.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition gallery is decorated as an ancient Egyptian
temple in which the exhibits are displayed under 12 topics. The
exhibition will run till January 17, 1999. 
</P>
