<HEADLINE> Israeli Soldiers Attack PNA Official in East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli soldiers on Monday
attacked a Palestinian cabinet minister and his body guards at
Ras Al-Amud of East Jerusalem, sources here said.
</P>
<P>
Faisal Husseini, Palestinian National Authority (PNA) minister
in charge of Jerusalem Affairs, and his body guards were staging a
sit-in at Ras Al-Amud against the construction there by a group of
Jewish people. Israeli soldiers beat them in an attempt to remove
them.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Israeli police at Ras Al-Amud prevented the Jewish
house builders from leveling the grounds there. But the builders
said on Monday that they have already received permission from the
Prime Minister's Office for house construction.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb Erekat on Sunday sent a
letter to Israel's Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh, urging Israel
to halt housing construction in Ras Al-Amud and give peace a
chance.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said in the letter that the planned construction in Ras
Al-Amud by a team of Jewish people is a blatant violation not only
of the Wye River Memorandum signed late last month, but also of
the Oslo Accords and the transitional agreements which stipulate
halting unilateral measures.
</P>
<P>
Conflicts also erupted on Sunday at Ras Al-Amud when several
members of Israeli Peace Now group tried to move away the fence
set up several days ago by a group of Israeli Knesset (parliament)
right-wing members. As a result, three Peace Now members were
arrested by police.
</P>
<P>
The planned housing construction in Ras Al-Amud has caused
another political dispute between the Palestinians and Israel. The
Palestinian side has strongly opposed such a move, stating that
East Jerusalem is part of the occupied territory and the Israeli
side has no right to build any house there.
</P>
<P>
Some four months ago, Israel's Jerusalem municipality issued
permits to build 132 departments for Jewish housing on an empty
plot in Ras Al-Amud, which is said to be owned by American
millionaire Irving Moskowitz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
