<HEADLINE> Indonesian Police Chief Orders Crackdown on Outlaws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Chief of the Indonesian Police
Lt. Gen. Roesmanhadi Monday ordered a crackdown on those who
commit unconstitutional acts that could undermine the country's
integrity.
</P>
<P>
The police will not take any risk by allowing outlawed groups
to carry out their actions, Roesmanhadi said in a written speech
read in Palembang, capital of South Sumatra province, before
security personnel tasked to safeguard this province during the
special session of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR).
</P>
<P>
The MPR is scheduled to hold a special session on November 10
to 13 in Jakarta to discuss next year's general, presidential and
vice presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
Various parties in the country have been at odds over the need
for the event, with some demanding that it be canceled. Student
protests flared again in the capital last week, demanding the
resignation of President B.J. Habibie and saying the special
session of MPR should not go ahead.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Roesmanhadi said the economic crisis has led to
a rise in the incidence of crime and social unrest in many parts
of the country.
</P>
<P>
However, such crimes as killings, kidnappings and riots, which
have caused huge losses, were not purely triggered by the crisis,
he was quoted by Antara News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that these destructive actions can never solve the
country's economic difficulties but will only make the people
suffer all the more.
</P>
<P>
The country must thus find constructive solutions to the
crisis, he added. 
</P>
