<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Delays Implementation of Interim Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The latest interim accord
between Israel and the Palestinians saw the first delay Monday in
its implementation as Israel said the deal would not go into
effect before being ratified by the cabinet and the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said that according to
Israel's legal constraints, the accord became effective only after
it was approved by the cabinet and the Knesset, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
This means that the implementation of the agreement, which
should begin Monday according to the time line agreed upon, would
be delayed for at least several days.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who postponed a cabinet voting on the agreement
last week, is expected to present the accord to the cabinet for
ratification Tuesday and to the Knesset next week.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) endorsed the agreement
in a cabinet meeting last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that he would make effort to make sure the delay
in the implementation would be short. Reports said Washington has
accepted Israel's position on the delay.
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat, however, stressed
that the implementation should start Monday as scheduled in the
agreement, signed by Netanyahu and PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat on
October 23.
</P>
<P>
The agreement stipulated that it would come into force 10 days
from its signing regardless of ratification.
</P>
<P>
Erekat told Israel Radio that he was sorry that Netanyahu was
preparing grounds for not honoring the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon, who was to
meet with Palestinian negotiator Mohammed Abbas (Abu Mazen) Monday
to discuss interim matters, canceled the meeting Sunday night
citing illness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
