<HEADLINE> U.S. Peace Envoys to visit Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. senior officials in
charge of the Mideast affairs will visit Lebanon next week in an
effort to revive the stalled peace process, the Daily Star
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
A source with the Foreign Ministry said that the officials are
Assistant Secretary of State Martin Indyk and Middle East peace
envoy Dennis Ross.
</P>
<P>
The source said the specific date for the tour has yet to be
set and the officials may pay unscheduled visit to Lebanon as they
did before due to security reasons.
</P>
<P>
The officials are also expected to visit Syria, Israel and the
Palestinian self-rule territory, the source said.
</P>
<P>
They will go to Israel and the Palestinian territory to oversee
the implementation of the newly-signed peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Israel will pull back its troops from 13.1
percent more of the West Bank while the Palestinians intensify
their crackdown on Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
In Syria and Lebanon, the U.S. officials will hold talks with
the two countries' leaders to discuss the prospects of resuming
the peace talks with Israel, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between Syria, Lebanon and Israel have been
stalled since Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu came to
power in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Israel is occupying Golan Heights that it captured from Syria
in the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
It also carved out a self-declared security zone in southern
Lebanon in 1985 with the aim of protecting its north from
cross-border attacks by Lebanese guerrillas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
