<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli President Visits Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides and his Israeli counterpart Ezer Weizman said they were
confident in building closer cooperation and friendly ties between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Both presidents expressed their optimism at Larnaca
International Airport Monday morning in a welcoming ceremony for
Weizman, who came on a three-day state visit at the invitation of
Clerides.
</P>
<P>
Clerides described Weizman as his "good friend," saying "Cyprus
and Israel are already linked with bonds of friendship and close
cooperation."
</P>
<P>
"We look forward with confidence to an even closer cooperation
in bilateral, regional and international affairs," which not only
serves the interests of the peoples of Cyprus and Israel, but also
promotes and reinforces the cause of peace, security and stability
in this volatile region," Clerides said.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Weizman said "relations between our two peoples
go back to thousands of years to Roman times, when there was a
large Jewish community in Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased with the bilateral cooperation in economy,
commerce, agriculture." he added.
</P>
<P>
Weizman said the recent Palestinian-Israeli peace accord in
Washington was a very positive step toward a final settlement of
the disputes between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that soon we will hear that a solution has also been
found to your problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974, when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island
through a bi-communal formula, but peace talks between the two
sides have been deadlocked since last year.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Israel and Cyprus have been enhanced since
Cyprus opened its embassy in Tel Aviv five years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0082 </DOCNO>
