<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Refugees Blamed for Rise of Crimes in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Gu Ming)
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has blamed that
unlawful foreign refugees are causing more and more incidents of
robbery, rape and arson in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Kagera Region in the northwest, which borders Rwanda,
Burundi and Uganda, is one of the areas that bears the brunt of
attacks by illegal refugees.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months of this year, the region recorded 375
cases of robbery, compared to 337 during the same period last
year. Meanwhile, rape cases increased from 138 to 154 and arson
cases went up sharply from 43 to 151.
</P>
<P>
During January and September, the region also registered 152
murder incidents and 180 cases of cattle rustling.
</P>
<P>
The figures were revealed by Regional Commissioner Mohamed
Babu during a recent tour to the region.
</P>
<P>
For unknown reasons, a lot of refugees who were repatriated at
the end of 1996 had recently come back in thousands especially
from Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
At present, more than 4,400 Rwandans are taking shelter at
refugee camps in the Karagwe District while 110,585 Burundian
refugees are accomodated at the Ngara District.
</P>
<P>
Some of the refugees are collaborating with local bandits in
committing crimes such as armed robbery and ambush of vehicles.
Last Monday, an armed gang in an attack on four vehicles at
Nkenge area on the Kyaka-Bukoba road, robbed passengers of
properties and raped a 30-year-old woman.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Babu has appealed to the government to provide funds
to launch a special crackdown on the rampant bandits.
</P>
<P>
At present, the regional government has no option but to ask
the police to escort vehicles travelling on roads haunted by
bandits and order vehicles not to travel after 7:30 pm on those
roads.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye last week described
the problem of refugees as a headache to the government as they
not only caused economic burden but also worsened social security
and environmental situations.
</P>
<P>
At present, the country plays host to more than 300,000
refugees, mostly from the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC),
Burundi, Rwanda and Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The refugees are mainly accomodated in Kagera and Kigoma
regions. The Kigoma Regional Commissioner, Ukiwaona Ditopile
Mzuzuri, has also complained about armed banditry incidents
caused by refugees.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Tanzanian Foreign Minister Jakaya Kikwete urged
the international community to help Tanzania solve the problems
of refugees.
</P>
<P>
Recently, ambassadors of the United States, Japan, Denmark,
Britain, Germany and France, as well as U.N. representatives,
toured the Kigoma to see the situation of refugees there.
</P>
<P>
The trip, organized by the United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees and World Food Program, was aimed at winning
financial assistance from major donors to solve problems
related to refugees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibian Govt Unearthes Secession Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Namibian government
Monday claimed to have unearthed a plan, led by former opposition
leader Mishake Muyongo and Mafwe tribe chief Boniface Mamili, to
launch a rebellion to secede Caprivi, South African Press
Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Namibian Army Chif of Staff General Martin Shali said the
government had been monitoring the group.
</P>
<P>
He said there was no room for "terrorists" in Namibia and that
the Namibian Defense Force will deal with the "terrorists" in the
same way it was dealing with rebels in the Democratic Republic of
the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Namibian troops are in the DRC to help President Laurent
Kabila fight rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, 92 armed Namibians were arrested and detained in
Botswana after illegally entering the country, reportedly seeking
asylum.
</P>
<P>
Another 12 crossed into Botswana last Thursday, saying they
needed protection.
</P>
<P>
They were being held at Kasane on the border between Namibia
and Botswana.
</P>
<P>
The Mafwe are one of five tribes living along the Zambezi and
Kwando riverbanks to the northeast of Namibia.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Turnhalle Alliance, of which Muyongo was
leader, has previously distanced itself from secession attempts.
</P>
</TEXT>
