<HEADLINE> S. African Troops Begin Withdrawal From Lesotho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 2 (Xinhua) -- South Africa began
withdrawing its troops from Lesotho Monday morning, with the
first 500 soldiers having returned to South Africa, South African
radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,400 of the 3,500 troops deployed in Lesotho will pull
out of the mountain kingdom by Wednesday, operation acting
commander Jimmy Masisi was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
South African National Defense Force chief General Siphiwe
Nyanda announced the withdrawal last weekend. He said the
improved situation in Lesotho required the reduction of forces in
Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
Some 600 lightly armed South African soldiers will be sent in
to relieve the 1,400 troops.
</P>
<P>
South African and Botswanan troops entered Lesotho on
September 22 under the auspices of the Southern African
Development Community to help the Lesotho government quell rising
unrest in the country.
</P>
<P>
Trouble in the mountain kingdom started after the Lesotho
opposition protested against the results of the May 23 general
election, claiming that they were rigged in favor of the ruling
Lesotho Congress for Democracy.
</P>
<P>
The unrest boiled up to a major political crisis in
mid-September when junior military officers launched a mutiny and
forced senior officers, including Lesotho Defense Force chief
Makhule Mosakeng, to resign at gun point. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
