<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Government Committed to Curbing Air Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government has
stressed the need to combat air pollution and is committed to
improving the region's air quality.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Planning, Environment and Lands Bureau
noted on Sunday that Hong Kong's overall air quality is about the
same as many other major metropolis such as London and New York.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said: "our main problem is the very high density
of motor vehicles and the high diesel vehicle mileage that have
caused air pollution and nuisances at the roadside."
</P>
<P>
The government's proposal is to require a mandatory use of
liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) taxis as from the end of 2000 and
encourage all diesel taxis to be phased out within a 5-year
period.
</P>
<P>
Replacing diesel taxis by LPG taxis can reduce 30 percent of
the respirable suspended particulates emitted from motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the spokesman said the government is exploring a
package of new measures to deal with vehicle air pollution in a
comprehensive manner.
</P>
<P>
"We are also stepping up vehicle inspection and looking into
the feasibility of extending the use of LPG or other clean
alternative fuel vehicles to replace diesel vehicles," he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the government has begun to address the
issue of air pollution together with adjacent cities in the long
term.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has agreed with the Guangdong authorities to put up a
 joint study to look into the air pollution problem in a regional
perspective as well as to consider joint action and plans to stop
the air quality from deterioration, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mainland-HK Trade Enjoys Comprehensive Growth: Chinese Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The economic and trading
relations between China's interior and Hong Kong have enjoyed a
comprehensive development during the 20 years since China pursued
the policy of opening to the outside world, a Chinese official
said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Wang Hui, director-general of the Department of Taiwan, Hong
Kong and Macao of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation (MOFTEC) of China, said that the trade volume between
the interior and Hong Kong increased from 2.607 billion
U.S. dollars in 1978 to 50.771 billion U.S. dollars in 1997, which
 represented an 18-fold expansion.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the China Business Update Conference held Monday at
Hong Kong's Grand Hyatt Hotel, Wang said that in the first nine
months this year, the volume of export and import between the
mainland and Hong Kong amounted to 34.94 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The volume of the export from the mainland to Hong Kong was
30.12 billion U.S. dollars while the import from Hong Kong to the
mainland was 4.82 billion U.S. dollars, Wang said. Hong Kong is
now the third largest trading partner of the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hong Kong has become the most important source of
overseas investment for China, Wang added.
</P>
<P>
There had been 170,000 Hong Kong invested projects in the
mainland by the end of 1997 while in the past nine months this
year, 5,948 more Hong Kong funded companies had been approved by
authorities of the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Also at the conference, Shao Ning, director general of the
Department of Enterprises of the State Economic and Trade
Commission, said that the reform of China's state-owned
enterprises will provide more and more opportunities for overseas
investors to participate in China's economic development.
</P>
<P>
At present, Shao said, China's state-owned enterprises have set
up over 10,000 joint ventures with overseas investors and the
purchase of state-owned enterprises by overseas companies will
face no policy barriers at all.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of government officials, businessmen and scholars from
 China's mainland, Hong Kong and Taiwan as well as foreign
countries attended the one-day conference.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
