<HEADLINE> Northern Vietnam Reaping Autumn Rice Crop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in Vietnam's northern
provinces harvested a total of 707,000 hectares of autumn rice, 60
percent of the cultivated area, by the end of October, Vietnam
News Agency (VNA) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in the Red River Delta have brought in 59 percent of
their planted area, VNA quoted the Ministry of Agriculture and
rural Development (MARD) as saying.
</P>
<P>
Officials predicted that Thai Binh province, located more than
100 km southeast of Hanoi, would produce between 5.3 and 5.4 tons
of rice per hectare.
</P>
<P>
This year foodstuff output for Thai Binh province, including
spring rice, autumn rice and other foodstuff crops, is a record
1.025 to 1.05 million tons.
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth year the province has harvested over 1
million tons of crops.
</P>
<P>
Along with harvesting their autumn rice, farmers in northern
provinces have also planted about 347,000 hectares of winter
crops.
</P>
<P>
As rainfall nationwide has only been 50 percent of the usual
yearly level, the MARD foresees a shortage of water throughout the
country, particlarly in northern and central regions.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has asked all localities to use water thriftily
and protect water resouces such as rivers, lakes, ponds and
reservoirs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
