<HEADLINE> Vietnam Exports 3.25 Million Tons of Rice by October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Rice volume loaded on board in
October was expected to be 200,000 tons, bringing Vietnam's total
export in the first ten months to 3.25 million tons, the Saigon
Times daily reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The English-language daily in Ho Chi Minh City quoted a
government official as saying that the rice export now is mostly
to fill a major deal with Indonesia and old contracts.
</P>
<P>
"New contracts have not been signed as Vietnam's export prices
are still high compared to falling prices in the world market,"
the official said.
</P>
<P>
Currently 25 percent broken grade is quoted 272-274 U.S.
dollars per ton F.O.B. Saigon Port, while in Bangkok quotations
of the same grade are at around 265-267 U.S. dollars a ton.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, five percent broken grade is offered at 287-290
dollars a ton, down from 295 dollars last week, the Saigon Times
daily said.
</P>
<P>
Local traders are now keen on the export of high-grade rice, as
they find trading of 25 percent broken grade too expensive due to
mounting domestic prices.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam plans to export 3.7-3.8 million tons of rice in 1999.
Up to 80 percent of the year's quotas will be allocated early with
20 percent by the end of the third quarter. 
</P>
