<HEADLINE> Philippine Congress Could Pass 1999 Budget Before </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Estrada administration
expressed its confidence Monday that the congress can pass the
proposed 579.5 billion peso (14 billion U.S. dollars) national
budget for 1999 before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
In a report published here Monday, Secretary Benjamin Diokno of
the Department of Budget and Management said that the close
coordination between the executive department and the congress
would likely lead to the swift passage of the national budget for
1999.
</P>
<P>
He said the swift passage is likely as the Senate started
hearings even before it formally received the proposed budget from
the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
"When we resume (congressional deliberations on the budget) on
November 9, the moment the budget is submitted to us, then we will
already have a head start and we expect to use up less time in
order to act on the budget," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The House (of Representatives) passed the budget proposed by
President (Joseph) Estrada virtually intact, so we can see here
the close coordination between the executive and the congress,"
Diokno said.
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives approved on second reading on
October 24 the proposed 1999 budget without making major changes
to the Estrada administration's proposal.
</P>
<P>
The House will approve the proposed budget on third and final
reading when it resumes session next week.
</P>
<P>
The budget proposal will then go to the Senate for further
deliberations and approval.
</P>
<P>
"So we are hopeful that it will be approved before the
Christmas break on December 23," Diokno said. 
</P>
