<HEADLINE> Philippines to Address Shortage of School Principals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
taking steps to address the shortage of school principals by
adopting the concept of integrated schools, among other remedial
measures.
</P>
<P>
In a report released by the presidential office here Monday,
Secretary Andrew Gonzalez of the Department of Education said that
at present 3,458 elementary schools and almost half of the
secondary schools in the country have no principals or even head
teachers to supervise academic functions.
</P>
<P>
According to Gonzalez, only 24 percent or 8,637 of the
country's 35,516 elementary schools are headed by full-fledged
principals.
</P>
<P>
The shortage of principals is worse in secondary schools as
only 53.44 percent or 2,089 of 3,909 schools have principals, he
said.
</P>
<P>
To resolve this shortfall, he said, his department has proposed
the adoption of the following schemes:
</P>
<P>
-- the appointment of a school-based head for big central
schools;
</P>
<P>
-- the designation of a non-school-based head, such as cluster
heads and district supervisors, for small schools in remote areas;
and
</P>
<P>
-- the integration of an elementary and a secondary school
under the concept of integrated schools.
</P>
<P>
He said that his department has appealed to the congress to
uphold the Estrada administration's proposal giving the education
sector the lion's share of the 1999 budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
