<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Trade Conference Opens in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, November 2 (Xinhua) -- A four-day Asian regional
conference of the International Federation for Alternative Trade
(IFAT) opened here Monday with focus on grass-roots producers.
</P>
<P>
Eighty-four participants from 16 countries are attending the
conference organized by the Fair Trade Group of Nepal under the
slogan of "The Present Scenario of Fair Trade: A Threat to the
Grass-roots Producers."
</P>
<P>
Eric Rozario, IFAT executive committee member, said that the
conference, the second of its nature, aims to promote regional
cooperation for grass-roots producers and work out reasonable and
workable solution to the problems facing them.
</P>
<P>
IFAT Chair Paul Myers said that the purpose of the IFAT which
is based in England is to improve the livelihood of the
disadvantaged groups all over the world, in particular those in
the developing countries, through the promotion of traditional
skill-oriented handicrafts and market management.
</P>
<P>
The IFAT now has 120 non-governmental organizations involved in
income-generation programs based on children and women of 45
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Fair Trade Group of Nepal, which joined the IFAT 22 years
ago, is an association of grass-roots producers of traditional
products in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
It aims to help women and other disadvantaged classes generate
income by adopting fair trade policies with focus on indigenous
raw materials and handicrafts based on traditional skills.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, a "fair trade" trade fair was organized on
handicrafts made by women from the participating countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Generate Electricity From Wood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will launch a trial
project to generate electricity from wood to overcome an
anticipated electricity shortage, according to the Forest
Department Monday.
</P>
<P>
The new project will be funded 394,000 U.S. dollars by the
European Union while the Sri Lankan government will provide
156,000 U.S. dollars, the department sources said.
</P>
<P>
An overall area of 36 hectares has been identified for the
project. The endeavor if proved a success would save 220,000
dollars in foreign exchange annually in the country, and will
result in the establishment of dendro thermal power plants that
will utilize biomass, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has the facility to harvest 10 million metric tons of
wood annually which is equal to 2.5 million of heat unit produced
by oil, the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
