<HEADLINE> Iranian Army Starts Final Stage of Grand Maneuver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian army started the
final stage of the Zulfaqar-2 military war games Monday morning
along the country's eastern border with Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency IRNA reported that the war games
were launched in the Zabol operation zone, the southeastern
province of Sistan-Baluchestan which borders Afghanistan and
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Some 200,000-strong forces, hundreds of tanks and armored
personnel carriers as well as tens of fighters and helicopters
took part in this stage of the military exercises, IRNA said.
</P>
<P>
Air attack of air-force fighters and helicopters and that of
armored and infantry forces on the positions of the mock enemy
are parts of the final stage of the maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
The Zulfaqar-2 maneuver, the biggest one launched by the
Iranian army since the Islamic Revolution in 1979, was kicked
off Saturday night after a month-long delay.
</P>
<P>
The maneuver was scheduled to be launched by end of September
in an area of 5,000 square kilometers amid tension between Iran
and the Afghan Taliban militia who killed nine Iranian diplomats
and reporter in northern Afghanistan in August.
</P>
<P>
It was postponed after the U.N. Secretary General's special
envoy on Afghan affairs Lakhdar Brahimi succeeded in persuading
the Taliban to repatriate the remains of the killed Iranians and
release 51 Iranian hostages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Currency Trading, Root Cause of Financial Crisis: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Monday described currency trading as the root
cause of the present financial crisis, saying unless this is
recognized corrective action cannot be taken to solve the
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"If currency trading cannot be done away with, then it should
be properly supervised and regulated," he said in a keynote
address at a luncheon held in conjunction with a two-day
international conference on "Managing the Asian Financial Crisis:
Lessons and Challenges" which opened here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said currency trading in the present form was not
essential even though exchanging one currency for another was
necessary for world trade.
</P>
<P>
"There is no reason why the world cannot act in concert to
regulate currency trading," said Mahathir, who is also the first
finance minister.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said, "This is possible if the big rich economic
powers are willing to cooperate, to enact laws and rules and to
enforce them."
</P>
<P>
He said the rules and regulations and laws would obviously
prevent the traders from making the kind of profit they were used
to making.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that currency trading must be forced into the
open and the world must act in concert to prevent money
laundering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
