<HEADLINE> Iran Slams Arafat for Signing Accord with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 2 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iranian official has
lashed out at Palestinian Leader Yasser Arafat for signing the
latest peace deal with Israel, local daily Tehran Times reported
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement is 100 percent in favor of Israel," deputy
foreign minister for Arab and African affairs, Mohammad Sadr, said
 in an interview with the conservative-prone newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Sadr said Arafat has become a policeman charged with ensuring
the security of Israel as a result of the agreement, signed in
Washington on October 23 after nine days of marathon negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Israel will withdraw from 13.1 percent of the
West Bank in three months while Palestinians convene the
Palestinian National Council to revoke anti-Israeli clauses in its
National Charter and crack down anti-Israeli terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
The accord broke a 19-month deadlock of the Palestinian-Israeli
peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Now, after signing this agreement both Arafat and Israel have
united for the Israeli security and for cracking down on the
genuine struggle against oppression," Sadr was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the agreement also creates a gulf among Palestinian
forces and allows Arafat to silence any voice against Israel. "It
has become the duty of Arafat to destroy all the movements for the
liberation of Palestine," Sadr said.
</P>
<P>
The security would not be for the region, but only for
Israel, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
