<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Fifty prisoners in a
high-security prison in the eastern Turkish province of Erzurum
have gone on a hunger strike demanding better conditions, Daily
News said Monday.
</P>
<P>
If no solution is found, hunger strikes may spread to other
Turkish prisons, Osman Baydemir of the Human Rights Association
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
They are demanding relative freedom of movement in prison,
better medical conditions and punishment of those wardens who
ill-treat prisoners, Baydemir said.
</P>
<P>
"We asked the prisoners not to take suicidal actions, such
as burning themselves," he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, three prisoner, convicted of being members
of the Kurdish Workers' Party, died after setting themselves on
fire.
</P>
<P>
However, a senior prison official said that the prisoners
enjoyed good treatment in jail and their real aim is to arouse the
public's attention. 
</P>
