<HEADLINE> Nepali Parliamentary Team Leaves For Bhutan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, November 2 (Xinhua) -- A four-member parliamentary
team of Nepal left here Monday for Bhutan for an official visit
which aims to create a conducive atmosphere for solving the
problems between the two Himalayan kingdoms including the refugee
issue.
</P>
<P>
Hiranya Lal Shrestha, chairman of the Lower House Foreign
Relations and Human Rights Committee and leader of the team, told
the press at the airport that the team visits Bhutan at the
invitation of Speaker of the Bhutanese National Assembly Kinzang
Dorjee.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is the first Nepalese parliamentary team to
visit Bhutan since 1990.
</P>
<P>
"This sort of interaction will help to create conducive
atmosphere to solve the problems like the Bhutanese refugee
problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The parliamentarians of both countries will try to influence
their respective governments to come into conclusion to resolve
the problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 Bhutanese refugees are staying in eight U.N.-run
camps in eastern Nepal after being forced to flee Bhutan in 1989
and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Seven rounds of ministerial talks had been held between the two
countries but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
India, which handles Bhutan's defense and foreign affairs, has
refused to get involved, saying it is a bilateral matter.
</P>
<P>
Shrestha said that he is hopeful that ministerial talks between
Nepal and Bhutan, stalled since 1996, will resume this year.
</P>
<P>
He said he will hand over a letter from Speaker Ram Chandra
Poudel to Dorjee inviting him to visit Nepal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
