<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Adults More Likely to Surf Internet at Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Australian adults are more
likely to surf the Internet at work than at home, an official
survey released here Monday found.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said Monday that 1.43
million people use the Internet at work, compared with 1.29
million who surf the world-wide web in their own time.
</P>
<P>
Another 1.7 million access the Internet at a mixture of places
such as universities, libraries, or a friend's or neighbor's
house.
</P>
<P>
The survey, taken in February and May this year, also found
that 3.34 million adults had been on-line in the 12 months before
they were questioned.
</P>
<P>
Australia's population totals 18 million.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that more households (43 percent) own a
mobile phone than a computer (37 percent) or an answering machine
(33 percent).
</P>
<P>
More than 1.7 million, or 50.5 percent, of all children aged
between five and 17 use a home computer more than once a week.
</P>
<P>
About 85 percent of the children who frequently use a home
computer spend their time playing games, compared with only 15
percent who are busy with Internet-based activities.
</P>
<P>
This compared to about one-quarter of adults who use a home
computer frequently, or 3.46 million.
</P>
<P>
The survey said that 15.4 percent, or 913,000 households,
access the Internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
