<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 09:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hamas Officials Deny Threatening Arafat's Reign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Senior officials of the
Islamic militant group Hamas have denied that its military wing
has threatened to turn its guns towards the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA), local radio and TV reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted a senior Hamas official in Gaza as denying
Sunday night that a leaflet faxed to some news organizations
carrying the warning earlier in the day came from the military or
political wing of Hamas.
</P>
<P>
A Hamas spokesman in Hebron, Abdel Khalek Natshe, also denied
the leaflet was authentic and accused Israel of fabricating it to
press the PNA to crack down further on the militants.
</P>
<P>
The leaflet, signed by Hamas' military wing, Izzedine al Qassem
Brigades, threatened violent retaliation against the PNA if it
continued to press its campaign against Hamas.
</P>
<P>
If the leaflet was true, it would be the first time that Hamas
has made a direct threat against the PNA. The militant
organization has said that it wanted to avoid confrontation among
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The extraordinary warning followed a roundup by Palestinian
security forces of Hamas' leadership and activists, launched last
week after PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat signed a land-for-peace deal
on October 23 in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The agreement calls for tougher Palestinian measures to fight
terrorism in exchange for further Israeli withdrawal from the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The crackdown was intensified after a failed suicide bombing in
Gaza on Thursday. More than 100 Hamas activists have been rounded
up and Hamas founder and spiritual leader Sheikh Ahmed Yassin has
been put under house arrest by Palestinian security forces.
</P>
<P>
The leaflet accused Arafat of having "reached the point of
treason" by moving against Hamas, calling for an immediate end to
the ongoing crackdown in order to spare Palestinians "the
horrors ... of civil war."
</P>
<P>
Palestinian security officials took the warnings seriously and
issued some of their own in response.
</P>
<P>
"We have only one authority in this land, which is the
Palestinian National Authority," Palestinian police chief Ghazi
Jabali said. "We are going to take all measures to control the
situation."
</P>
<P>
Tawfik Tarawi, head of the Palestinian general intelligence
service in the West Bank, also said that "I hope that it (the
leaflet) isn't true, but if this is Hamas' method we will react
strongly against any attempt to assault any security or police
officer." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise Sharply in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices in Tokyo posted a
sharp rise on the first day of trading in November with the Nikkei
index jumping by 2.86 percent Monday on news of more Japanese bank
restructuring at home and the resilience of the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange advanced 388.24 points to end
at 13,952.75, a high for the day and its highest close in more
than a week.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, gained 30.24 points or 2.92 percent to
1,065.84.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section remained small as investors kept
a wary eye on upcoming midterm earnings reports, with about 370
million shares being traded, almost unchanged from Friday.
</P>
<P>
Fuji Bank was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
All sectors, with the exception of marine and forestry
industries, enjoyed gains, traders said.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector led the market by rising 5.51 percent on new
signs that more large Japanese banks are seeking to trim their
overseas operations in order to beef up their capital.
</P>
<P>
Exporters also gained on news that the United States, a major
importer of Japanese cars and electronics goods, posted an
annualized 3.3 percent rise in gross domestic product for the
July-September quarter, surpassing analysts' forecasts.
</P>
<P>
Traders also attributed the exporters' strong showing to a
decision among the Group of Seven industrialized nations to create
a 90 billion U.S. dollar safety net to contain the crisis in
the emerging economies.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers outnumbered
losers 837 to 237, with 193 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
