<HEADLINE> First Liver Transplant in Mideast Succeeds in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese doctors in the
American University of Beirut have successfully performed a liver
transplant, the first of its kinds the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Doctors Mohammed Jawad Khalifch, Hani Hajji and Ghattas Khoury
worked for 18 hours and successfully transplanted the liver for a
three-year-old last Friday, the Daily Star reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The medication for the operation was shipped in from Cyprus,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference to announce the result of operation,
Khoury encouraged people to donate their organs and urged the
authorities to launch a campaign to encourage donors.
</P>
<P>
In July, Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri said that he
was willing to donate all his organs after his death and pledged
100,000 U.S. dollars to children with kidney failure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
