<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commemorating Forerunner of China's Science, Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- A group of Chinese scientists
gathered here today at prestigious Qinghua University to
commemorate the 180th anniversary of birth of Xu Shou, forerunner
of China's modern science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Xu, a native of Wuxi in east China's Jiangsu Province, was born
in 1818 and died in 1884, a period during which China was
suffering from invasion by imperialist powers.
</P>
<P>
Xu was a chemist, a munitions expert, a translator and an
educator. He devoted himself wholeheartedly to the natural
sciences for the purpose of making China more prosperous and
powerful.
</P>
<P>
Xu had a good command of languages, mathematics, physics,
chemistry and machinery, and stressed the importance of learning
from the advanced technologies of the Western countries.
</P>
<P>
Under Xu's guidance, China's first steamship, the "Huanghu,"
was launched at Nanjing in 1865.
</P>
<P>
He also guided the production of China's first group of warships
and first steam engine.
</P>
<P>
Participants at today's gathering also praised Xu's contributions
to introducing Western scientific and technological methods.
</P>
<P>
Most of Xu's descendants were also engaged in scientific
research. Xu's second son, Xu Jianyin, was a famous military
industry expert of modern China, who died experimenting with
smokeless gunpowder in 1901. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
