<HEADLINE> Commentary: One China Principle Is Undoubted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The diplomatic ties established
today between China and Tonga marks new progress for relations
between China and the countries of the South Pacific region, and
indicates the willingness of an increasing number of countries to
normalize ties with China under the One China principle.
</P>
<P>
Tonga recognizes that there is only one China, and the People's
Republic of China is the sole legitimate government representing
the whole of China, and Taiwan is an inalienable part of China,
according to a joint communique signed by the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Along with Tonga, there are now 11 countries of the 16-member
South Pacific Forum which have forged diplomatic links with China.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Cook Islands in the South Pacific, the Bahamas and
St. Lucia in the Caribbean, as well as South Africa, the Central
African Republic and Guinea-Bissau in Africa have all formed or
restored diplomatic relations with China since last year.
</P>
<P>
To date, there are 163 countries which have diplomatic
relations with the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
The normalization of relations between China and Taiwan's so-
called allies in these three regions shows that the One China
principle is undoubted, and that bilateral relations of
mutual benefit with China under the One China principle has become
a trend.
</P>
<P>
"St. Lucia has proceeded in a direction which the majority of
the countries of the world has already trod by establishing
diplomatic links with the People's Republic of China," said
St. Lucia's Prime Minister Kenny Anthony.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Premier Qian Qichen, in meeting with Koo Chen-fu,
chairman of Taiwan's Straits Exchange Foundation, two weeks ago,
said the fact that Taiwan's so-called international space is
narrowing is an inevitable result of the current situation,
and that the trend is ongoing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Blanket Amnesty in South Africa: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 2 (Xinhua) -- A senior South African
official has reiterated that there will be no general amnesty for
those who have been found responsible for gross human rights
violation during apartheid era, local daily Sowetan reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The South African government has "never considered blanket
amnesty because we believe it is not in the interest of the
people of South Africa", Justice Minister Dullah Omar was quoted
as saying Sunday.
</P>
<P>
However, Omar indicated that some important government
officials like Winnie Madikizela-Mandela and Mangosuthu
Buthelezi, who have been fingered in the TRC report for human
rights violations, might escape prosecution.
</P>
<P>
Madikizila-Mandela, normally called Winnie, is ex-wife of
South African President Nelson Mandela. Buthelezi, chairman of
the biggest black opposition party Inkatha Freedom Party,
currently is minister of home affairs in the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
"We are not going to be reckless because some of the people
mentioned, like Mrs Madikizela-Mandela and Dr. Buthelezi, are
important people who have played a significant role in this
country," Omar said.
</P>
<P>
He said the matter will be referred to the cabinet which will
develop guidelines on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Winnie and Buthelezi are but two in a long list of high
profile politicians who may be liable for prosecution. These
include the two apartheid era's presidents, P W Botha and F W De
Klerk.
</P>
<P>
Both Botha and De Klerk have not applied for amnesty.
</P>
<P>
In its 3,500-page final report issued last Friday, the Truth
and Reconciliation Commission (TRC) also said that the ruling African
National Congress should be responsible for gross human rights
violations in its struggle against apartheid both indisde and
outside the country.
</P>
<P>
President Mandela has accepted the report, but his deputy
Thabo Mbeki, who is also chairman of the ANC, described the
report as "wrong and misguided", and demanded for correction.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Buthelezi lauded the ANC for its legal action
against the TRC, saying the party was within its right to
challenge the contents of the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
