<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retired President Benefits Bill Not Law Yet: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The bill passed by the Ugandan
Parliament on the reduction of benefits of retired presidents is
not a law yet, the Public Relations Officer of the Parliament
Kagole Kivumbi told Xinhua in a telephone interview Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Kivumbi said: "According to the Consitution, a bill becomes a
law if the president gives consent to it. Usually, the president
will sign it within 30 days after it is passed by the
legislature."
</P>
<P>
When asked for the reasons for the slashed benefits for the
retired presidents, he said it should be based on the economic
situation of the country.
</P>
<P>
It should not be taken to mean that the economy does not
perform as well as in the past. It is a result of rationization,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The East African weekly reported that the Ugandan Parliament
passed a law reducing the retirement benefits of ex-presidents
and restricting movement and free education of the incumbent
president's offspring.
</P>
<P>
The decision was a result of debate on the Presidential
Emoluments and Benefits Bill tabled by Public Service Minister
Nuwa Amanya Mushega.
</P>
<P>
According to the bill, presidents who cease to hold office
other than for abuse of office or misconduct should get 2 million
Shillings (1,481 U.S. Dollars) per month on top of a fully
furnished house, government-paid chauffeur-driven car and free
medical treatment for self and immediate family.
</P>
<P>
Under the passed bill, retired presidents are now to get a
furniture allowance of 20 million shillings (14,815 Dollars)
every five years.
</P>
<P>
The legislature also endorsed 300,000 Shillings (222 Dollars)
per month as medical allowances for family and another 500,000
Shillings (371 Dollars) per month for utility costs.
</P>
<P>
If a retired president dies, the immediate family is entitled
to allowances equivalent to half of what the deceased president
is earning for six months onwards only.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said, the parliament did not change the
provision of the bill which entitles the head of state to a
monthly salary of 3.6 million Shillings (2,667 Dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Pursues Tight Monetary Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's central bank, the Bank
of Zambia (BOZ), has pursued a tight monetary policy to withdraw
excess funds from the public to curb the speculative demand and
unnecessary demand pressures on the foreign exchange supply.
</P>
<P>
This was confirmed by BOZ spokesman Kabinga Pande at the
weekend, state-controlled Times of Zambia reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
This policy, explained Panda, aimed to resolve the
contradiction between demand and supply on the country's forex
market and check the continuous depreciation of the local
currency Kwacha.
</P>
<P>
The local Kwacha has depreciated by more than 60 percent in
the past year from one U.S. Dollar against 1,300 at the end of
1997 to 2,100 Kwacha at present.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman attributed this to a number of factors like the
suspension of the balance of payments support by donors and the
low sales of the Zambian Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM), the
country's main foreign currency earner, as well as the seasonal
factor of increased demand of foreign exchange by the public as
the year end approaches.
</P>
<P>
Pande said that Zambia's export earnings have dropped due to
global El Nino effects which have adversely affected the
country's non-traditional exports.
</P>
<P>
External shocks such as the financial crisis in Asia is one of
the factors that have contributed to the falling of the local
currency on both the local and international markets, he added.
</P>
<P>
The combination of the low demand of copper and the reduced
prices on the world market have contributed to low foreign
exchange earnings, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the demand remains high on the local foreign exchange
market and the falling of the local currency has also seen the
rising of inflation, said the BOZ official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
