<HEADLINE> Ugandan Mayor Trial Opens in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The trial of the Kampala City
Mayor Nasser Sebaggala opens Monday in the new federal district
court of Massachusetts, the United States.
</P>
<P>
According to a New Vision report Monday, the trial
proceedings will be presided over by an African-American judge,
Regnald Lindsay and is expected to take up to three weeks.
</P>
<P>
The embattled mayor, who has been held in the U.S. since June
13, is represented by a team of lawyers led by Paul Kelly and
Eliot LLP.
</P>
<P>
The mayor is charged with eight counts, with four of which
related to alleged fraudulent checks, two to transportation of
false securities and two of false declarations to U.S. Customs.
</P>
<P>
The Prosecution alleged that the accused has a grand scheme to
defraud Bank Boston, a federally insured financial institution,
by means of false and fraudulent pretenses, representations and
promises.
</P>
<P>
The wife of the mayor, who is also the deputy speaker of the
city council, has flown to the U.S. to hear the trial.
</P>
<P>
She had reportedly threatened a Bank of Uganda official, who
is to testify against the mayor, with death, a charge she denied
immediately over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan authorities said earlier that Sebaggala had committed
some economic crimes also in Uganda, making his future as mayor
more uncertain.
</P>
<P>
Though democratically elected mayor of the capital in April,
he has been accused by opponents of lacking an A level
certificate required by the post. 
</P>
</TEXT>
