<HEADLINE> China Retains Asian Title in Chinese Chess </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIZHOU, China, November 2 (Xinhua) -- China retained the
men's Asian team title with a slim margin of 0.5 points at the
10th Chinese Chess Asian Championships which concluded here on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam ranked second in the week-long tournament, followed by
Hong Kong, China, Macau, Malaysia (West).
</P>
<P>
In the 13th and last round matches in the morning, three
Chinese players outwitted their opponents from the Philippines
with clear upperhands, while Vietnam outplayed Malaysia with two
wins and one draw.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, China, Chinese Taipei defeated Japan and Brunei
respectively with three straight wins, while Singapore, Macau
downed Myanmar and Thailand with two wins against one loss.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday night, Hong Kong, China forced Vietnam to share the
points with one win one draw and one loss, helping China to claim
the title virtually as China had only drawn once against Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Ranked sixth to eighth were Chinese Taipei, Myanmar and
Singpore, while the Philippines, Thailand, Japan, Malaysia (East)
and Brunei finished ninth to 13th respectively.
</P>
<P>
A total of 61 players from 13 countries and regions competed
in the tournament which featured women's singles, junior
individual and men's team titles. 
</P>
