<HEADLINE> SADC Allied Forces to Launch Offensive in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The allied forces of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) have resolved to
embark on an offensive campaign in the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC) aimed at clearing rebels backed by Rwanda and Uganda
from the eastern parts of the DRC.
</P>
<P>
This was announced Sunday by Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe in Lubumbashi of southern DRC at the end of an urgent
meeting called to review the may forward in view of the collapse
of peace talks in Lusaka last week, the Daily Herald reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting in Lubumbashi was attended by presidents Sam
Nujoma of Namibia and Laurent Kabila of the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the allied forces, Mugabe said they had
decided to go on an enemy clearance mission in search of lasting
peace.
</P>
<P>
Angolan President Eduardo dos Santos did not attend the
meeting, but was said to be in agreement with the allied forces'
resolution to flush rebels out of the DRC, the third largest
country on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
"What we are going into is the third phase of the struggle
aimed at protecting the sovereignty of the Congo. We are going
on the clearance of the enemy (rebels and their backers) from the
territory," Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
He would not give operational details on how the onslaught
would be launched but confirmed that forces from the three
countries -- Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe -- had already been
deployed in the east, following a resolution taken in Harare
prior to the failed Lusaka summit and aimed at halting conquest
moves in the eastern parts of the vast Great Lakes country.
</P>
<P>
The allied forces have already taken their position and are
expected to launch a heavy offensive against rebel-held positions
any time this week. The attacks will be aimed at retaking the
captured towns and flushing rebels and their backers out of the
DRC.
</P>
<P>
"During the second phase of the struggle, we decided to go
east. As we were discussing in Harare, preparations were going
on. That decision has since been implemented. We now have
troops in towns like Bujimayi, among others," said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
"We were disappointed by the stance taken by Rwanda during the
recent Lusaka meeting, denying that it had any of its troops in
the Congo. That did not make it possible to discuss any peace
accord," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
