<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guilin: China's Model for Sustainable Development of Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
GUILIN, November 2 (Xinhua) -- In a recent environmental
assessment of 46 key Chinese cities conducted by the National
Administration of Environmental Protection, the city of Guilin led
the list in environmental quality.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that this famous tourist Mecca has found the right
road to sustainable growth for its tourist industry by protecting
its environment.
</P>
<P>
Located along the Lijiang River of South China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region, this city of 500,000 people is known
worldwide for its natural scenery and cultural heritage. In 1997
alone, the city played host to more than 7 million overseas and
domestic travelers.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1970s, however, the poetic Lijiang River was
contaminated by industrial pollution. When Deng Xiaoping, who was
in charge of the country's industrial production at that time,
visited Guilin, he saw that an overwhelming amount of foul smoke
and wastewater was about to turn the people's fond memory of the
city into a thing of the past, permanently.
</P>
<P>
"We will lose more than we get if we pollute the Lijiang
River, no matter how fast we develop industries," he said. And
under his directions, the State Council made a decision for
"Restoring and Protecting the Environment of Guilin."
</P>
<P>
Environmental protection is now a 10-year-old national policy
in China. Guilin, in order to maintain its natural beauty and
promote the balanced growth of tourism without endangering the
environment, has beefed up pollution-control efforts and
investment in environment-friendly industries.
</P>
<P>
It has closed 49 factories and mills in recent years and built
142 foul-water processing systems to ensure a clean Lijiang River,
and more than 200,000 yuan (24,000 US dollars) of special funds
has been allocated annually for planting trees along the river
banks.
</P>
<P>
Despite financial turmoil in southeast Asia, Guilin continues
to attract tourists at a record rate. According to official
sources, the city's income from international travelers reached
1.18 million yuan in 1997, 11.9 percent more than 1996. Tourism
revenue now accounts for 15.14 percent of the city's GDP value.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Desert Control Unveils Ancient Great Wall in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Bai Chunlan, a farmer living
on the edge the Mu Us, China's third largest desert, was greatly
surprised when an archaeologist told him that the dirt wall in
front of his courtyard is a section of the Great Wall built over
1,400 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists say that a two-month field investigation proves
that this 25-kilometer section of the Great Wall is the remains of
a 350-kilometer Great Wall built in the Sui Dynasty (581-618
A.D.), the only section of the Great Wall dating to the Sui
Dynasty discovered.
</P>
<P>
This new discovery coincides with historical records on the
Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
Differing from other sections of the Great Wall, this part is
of a dark-red color and built of piled-up soil.
</P>
<P>
The newly discovered section is about 1 to 2.8
meters high and 5 to 13 meters wide. It also has a protective
ditch beside the outer portion of the Wall.
</P>
<P>
Bai, a Shabian Village farmer in Yanchi County in the Ningxia
Hui Autonomous Region, said he never dreamed that the tree
planting and crop growing done by his family, the only household
in the area for over a dozen years ago would result not only in
harvests, but in helping to unveil a part of the Great Wall buried
in the sand for many centuries.
</P>
<P>
Helped by scientists, Bai's family planted 16,000 trees and
grass over vast desert areas during the past decade. Together with
the efforts of other farmers, the one-tree village has turned into
an oasis.
</P>
<P>
The local government also funded the building of irrigation
channels along the edge of desert.
</P>
<P>
Bai's family also used ground water from a well to irrigate
wheat and maize.
</P>
<P>
The Great Wall surfaced from the ground gradually with the
enlargement of the shelter forest and the growing of crops.
</P>
<P>
The Great Wall has a total length of around 6,000
kilometers. Archeologists believe that most of the remains of the
ancient Great Wall in northwest China has been sleeping under the
desert.
</P>
<P>
China has serious desertification problems and the desert land
in the country expands by 2,460 square kilometers each year.
</P>
<P>
To curb the expansion of deserts, China has built a
4,480-kilometer-long shelter forest or so-called "Green Great
Wall" in the past 20 years in provinces and autonomous region in
northern China.
</P>
<P>
Lei Renze, Director of the Ningxia Regional Bureau of Cultural
Relics, said that although the newly discovered section of the
Great Wall is only a small part of the Wall, it is a good
beginning for more discoveries and the bureau has drawn up a
detailed plan for protecting the Great Wall.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0166 </DOCNO>
