<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Region Renews Land Contract System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in 9,326 villages, or 89
percent of the total number in north China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region, have renewed the land contract system with
local governments.
</P>
<P>
With farmland expanded to 4.7 million hectares, Inner Mongolia
is now a rising grain producer. Since the region introduced the
initiative-based land contract responsibility system in 1979, it
has become more than self-sufficient in grain, and on average has
supplied 3 billion kilos of grain annually to other parts of China
over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the central-government policy, at the
beginning of this year the regional government began to sign
renewed land contracts for another 30 years with farmers wishing
to do so.
</P>
<P>
The practice aims at stabilizing the household responsibility
contract system and arousing farmers' initiative for growing grain
crops.
</P>
<P>
With contracts renewed, farmers are willing to invest more in
contracted plots, and many raised funds to drill water wells,
improve soil and build irrigation canals and river dams.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Firms to Be Allowed to Buy Back ECBs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 2 (Xinhua) -- India's Union Finance
Ministry is likely to allow selected corporations to buy back the
outstanding external commercial borrowings (ECBs) at an attractive
discount, official sources said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
As a safeguard against net outflow of foreign exchange, the
ministry would restrict the usage of this facility only to
corporations which have sufficient export receivables to finance
such deals.
</P>
<P>
Spreads are inversely proportional to the price of the bonds.
Accordingly, if the yields go up, there is a commensurate decline
in the price of the bonds - precisely what happened after
international investor sentiment turned adverse following the
Southeast Asian currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
In January, the Finance Ministry had briefly permitted
corporations to repurchase outstanding foreign loans. A
Mumbai-based industrial house had taken the opportunity to put out
an offer to repurchase over 300 million U.S. dollars of its
outstanding loans. It had sought to finance the deal by floating a
syndicated loan.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry later discontinued the facility in the
wake of rising pressure on the rupee (local currency).
</P>
<P>
In recent months, however, the spreads have widened further,
rendering repurchase of the outstanding bonds attractive.
</P>
<P>
The new ECBs facility has been restricted only to structural
loans or bonds and debentures, and not allowed for syndicated
loans, the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
