<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Foreign Investment Back on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The first three quarters of
this year saw 1,100 new foreign investment projects launched in
Shanghai despite the impact of the Asian financial crisis,
according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
The contractual foreign investment in Shanghai between January
and September amounted to 5.1 billion U.S. dollars, about equal to
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
International giants such as Unilever, Volkswagen and Intel
have increased their investment by 1.26 billion dollars, said an
official in charge of Shanghai's foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, more than half the world's top 100 industrial
enterprises have projects in Shanghai, indicating rising
foreign-investor confidence in China over other Asian countries
and regions, some analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that about 3.68 billion U.S. dollars went to the
manufacturing sector, a 2.2-fold increase over the same period
last year, while the service sector, especially in properties,
declined due to adjustments in the investment structure made by
the municipal government.
</P>
<P>
Investment from the Asia-Pacific Region in the first nine
months decreased by 57.8 percent on an year-to-year basis, and
that of Japan was down 80 percent, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
However, the United States and Europe markedly expanded their
investment, and the U.S. and Germany have become the
major investors in Shanghai, accounting for 60 percent of the
city's total foreign investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
