<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dental Diseases Prevalent in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Dental diseases are becoming
prevalent in the Tibet Autonomous Region, according to a recent
survey conducted by the Hunan Medical Sciences University in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
A medical examination to 477 Tibetan children between the ages
of seven and sixteen in Nyalam and Yadong counties in the
autonomous region showed that more than 60 percent of these
children suffer from dental caries.
</P>
<P>
According to survey director Cao Jin, the incidence of caries
in the region has reached the level of many modern cities in
China, and is on the rise.
</P>
<P>
Cao explained that with improved living conditions, Tibetans in
the richer areas have changed some aspects of their diets and now
consume more sugar. But they know little about dental protection
and are more vulnerable to dental diseases.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of dental fluorosis, however, usually
found in poorer regions, has greatly dropped to 25.86 percent and
17.18 percent among children in the two places surveyed, compared
with over 70 percent in the less developed regions of Tibet, said
Cao.
</P>
<P>
Experts have advised related departments to enhance medical
knowledge of residents in the autonomous region and help Tibetans
form good health habits.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji's Economy Remains in Recession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Fiji's economy remains in
recession with output expected to contract by between three
percent and four percent this year, the Dominion reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper quoted a latest news statement
issued by the Reserve Bank of Fiji in Suva as saying the cause of
the recession has been the eight-month-old drought which sees
sugar production fall this year by about 50 percent to the lowest
level in 30 years. The drastic reduction of sugar production has
affected other sectors of Fiji's economy.
</P>
<P>
Another cause is the impact of global economic conditions,
which have deteriorated sharply with many countries now either in
recession or with falling growth rates.
</P>
<P>
Fiji usually earns almost 150 million U.S. dollars from sugar,
the backbone of its economy, but industrial sources in Fiji
expect this would be halved this year because the prolonged
drought has destroyed thousands of hectares of sugar cane.
</P>
<P>
But, despite this, Fiji's foreign exchange reserves remains
strong, the Reserve Bank of Fiji said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the main features of Fiji's economy in
the past six months were the economy staying in recession:
foreign exchange reserves were strong; the exchange rate remained
competitive; consumption was weak and fell; wage increases were
moderate; and the agricultural sectors was weak but the tourism
and garment industries performed well.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment Rate in New Zealand Keeps Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The unemployment rate in New
 Zealand rose from 7.7 percent in June to 8.1 percent in September
and is expected to peak at 8.8 percent in the middle of next year,
the Evening Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper quoted a local economist as
saying that a weak domestic economy, troubled offshore markets
and tariff cuts are the main reasons for the lengthening jobless
queue.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures for June released by New Zealand's
Household Labor Force Survey, 140,600 New Zealanders were out of
work, WestpacTrust economist Paul Gardiner said. Data from the
latest survey for September, due to be released on Thursday, will
show unemployment has risen above eight percent to 147,600, he
added.
</P>
<P>
"Such a result will see the unemployment rate rise from 7.7
percent in June to 8.1 percent in September, the highest level
since the 1991 recession," Gardiner said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the labor market tends to lag behind economic
activity and therefore he expected the unemployment rate to move
higher in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
"We expect the unemployment rate to peak at 8.8 percent in the
middle of next year," Gardiner said.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate in New Zealand would fall to 7.5 percent
by March 2000, according to the WestpacTrust economist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
