<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Planning Commission Cuts Growth Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 2 (Xinhua) -- India's Planning Commission
has cut growth targets for some sectors in the Ninth Five-Year
Plan (1998-2002) due to the industrial slowdown in the country,
Business Standard Monday quoted official sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The growth target for the manufacturing sector during the
period has been slashed from an annual average growth of 9.7
percent to 8.5 percent. This means much reduced growth in
1998-2002 compared with the Eight Five-Year Plan period, when
manufacturing sector crossed the targeted 9.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The final draft of the plan envisages a reduction in the growth
target of gross domestic product (GDP) from 7 to 6.7 percent per
year. The commission has also changed the growth projections for
the transportation industry and savings by the public, household
and private corporate sectors. The biggest cut is in the growth
target for public sector savings - from 2.8 to 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The plan panel has decided to decrease the growth target of
10.6 percent for electricity, gas and water marginally. But it
will keep the agriculture growth target of 4.5 percent intact.
"Though agriculture has not done as well as was expected, this
sector is capable of bouncing back and showing much higher growth
rates in the next three years," said an expert.
</P>
<P>
The Planning Commission is expected to submit the draft for
approval by the Union cabinet in the second week of this month.
The reasons for revising the GDP target are the recent salary
hikes of central and State government officials and the industrial
slowdown of 1997-98. "The rate of industrial growth was 5 percent
last year and is expected to be 5.5 percent this year. We do not
expect a dramatic improvement in the next three years of the Ninth
Five-Year Plan," a plan panel expert said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
