<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Discuss Trade Imbalance with Bangkok </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Trade imbalance against Dhaka is
expected to top the agenda for the forthcoming meeting of
Bangladesh-Thailand Joint Commission (JC) to be held in Thai
capital of Bangkok, press reports here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad will leave here
for Bangkok Tuesday as head of a team to the sixth meeting of the
JC established in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Azad and his Thai counterpart will review the entire spectrum
of bilateral relations as well as regional and international
issues of common concern, officials were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to exchange views on the areas of cooperation
of the BIMSTEC (Bangladesh-India-Myanmar-Sri Lank-Thailand
Economic Cooperation), a new regional grouping launched in Bangkok
in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
The JC meeting would discuss the overall bilateral trade,
paying special attention to a huge gap in the two-way trade, they
said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Bangladesh imported goods worth 135.86 million U.S.
dollars from Thailand and exported items valued at 14.57 million
dollars to that country.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi side is likely to request Thailand to purchase more
commodities from the country in a move to remove the imbalance in
trade in phases.
</P>
<P>
The commodities Bangladesh can export to Thailand in larger
quantum include tea, jute goods, shrimps, frozen fish, crabs,
tortoise, leather, jute yarn, twin and readymade garments.
</P>
<P>
The two sides may discuss ways for increasing trade through
private sectors.
</P>
<P>
Matters relating to fish projects and investment in Bangladesh
will also come up for discussion in the meeting, they said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the meeting agenda will include liquefied petroleum
gas project, maritime, cooperation and civil aviation affairs,
they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
