<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Passenger Plane Conducts Forced Landing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 2 (Xinhua) -- A passenger plane of China
Eastern Airlines made a successful emergency landing today after a
mechanical problem was found shortly after take-off.
</P>
<P>
The A300 passenger plane, flight No. 2322, which was scheduled
to fly to Osaka of Japan, took off from the Hongqiao Airport at
9:45 this morning but was forced to land after attempts to solve
the mechanical problem at the front landing chassis came to no
avail.
</P>
<P>
The plane, which was carrying 87 passengers, including 55
Japanese and one passenger from Taiwan, and 15 crew members,
landed at the airport at 12:03. No one was killed or injured.
</P>
<P>
The airport, which was closed at 11:50, was re-opened after the
plane's successful emergency landing.
</P>
<P>
A similar accident occurred on September 10 when a MD-11 plane,
which was carrying 120 passengers and 17 crew members, was found
to have a landing gear problem shortly after takeoff. In that
accident, nine passengers suffered superficial injuries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
