<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Ranks First in Coffee Export in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has become the biggest
coffee exporter in Asia and ranks second in Asia in terms of
coffee production, local media reports said.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam exported over 390,400 tones of coffee beans in the
1997-98 crop, earning more than 594 million U.S. dollars. The
annual coffee crop lasts from October to September of the
following year.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's coffee exports increased by 13 percent in quantity
and 43.5 percent in value compared with the previous crop.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's coffee has been shipped to 52 countries worldwide
with 82 percent going to the United States, Germany, Spain,
Britain, Italy, Poland, France, Austria, the Republic of Korea and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Vietnam has about 300,000 hectares of coffee and
plans to expand the acreage to 350,000 hectares by 2005 to bring
the national coffee output to 420,000-450,000 tones per crop.
</P>
<P>
The reports said this year's prolonged drought may cause losses
of 80,000-100,000 tones of beans in the coming 1998-1999 crop.
However, coffee growers still cherish a hope to harvest
380,000-400,000 tones of beans and export 560 million dollars of
coffee in the 1998-1999 crop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
