<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Astronauts Put Sun-Gazing Satellite Into Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Two U.S. astronauts Sunday
released the sun-gazing Spartan satellite into space,
accomplishing a job left over from last year.
</P>
<P>
Spartan, on its second shuttle flight in less than a year,
was supposed to spend two days studying the sun last November in
an orbit near the shuttle, but a series of mistakes by astronauts
rendered it useless, and two astronauts had to go out to get it
back.
</P>
<P>
NASA said that that mistake will not happen again, as they have
improved the computer software for Spartan and the directions for
its release from the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
Astronaut Stephen Robinson used the 50-foot robot arm to drop
the satellite into space, with help from Dr. Scott Parazynski on
the computers.
</P>
<P>
The 3,000-pound satellite did a pirouette as it entered space,
suggesting that everything was working properly. Discovery then
slowly backed away. The release took place at 340 miles (547
kilometers) over Baja, California.
</P>
<P>
The 11 million U.S. dollar satellite will collect images of the
sun's outer atmosphere, the corona, and charged particles
streaming from the sun out into the space. 
</P>
</TEXT>
