<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Parties Form State Coalition Governmet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Both the German Social
Democratic Party and the Party for Democratic Socialism (PDS) have
endorsed a pact reached on Saturday to form a coalition government
in Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania State.
</P>
<P>
The endorsement of the pact by the two parties has cleared all
hurdles for the PDS's return to the state-level government since
Germany's reunification in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The Social Democrats approved the pact Saturday at a conference
in the eastern German state, with 61 of the 91 delegates attending
the conference voted for the pact.
</P>
<P>
The PDS endorsed the pact with a two-third majority in its
conference at Parchim. A hundred out of the 114 delegates at the
conference voted in favor of the deal.
</P>
<P>
The PDS is the successor to the former Communist Party in the
former East Germany before the fall of the Berlin Wall.
</P>
<P>
Harald Ringstorff, Social Democrats' Minister-President nominee
in the state of Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania, expressed his
satisfaction over the voting.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on a coalition government with the PDS includes
"unprecedented social democratic policies," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ringstorff is expected to be elected Minister-President of the
new state government on Tuesday by the state legislature.
</P>
<P>
Gregor Gysi, leader of the PDS group in German parliament,
described the pact's approval as a "historic turning point," which
set a precedent in the political process in the eastern part of
Germany.
</P>
<P>
But the PDS is still an opposition party in the federal
republic as a whole, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Social Democrats seized 27 and the PDS 20 of the 71 seats
in the state legislature in the September 27 state legislature
election. The two parties jointly enjoy an overwhelming majority
in the newly elected state legislature. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
