<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-Up: Myanmar Strives to Develop Tourism Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government has been
taking various measures for the development the tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is rich in scenic beauties and cultural heritage. It
boasts of many tourist attractions including the world known
Shwedagon Pagoda, Mandalay royal city and Bagan, a city of
pagodas.
</P>
<P>
Despite its rich resources, Myanmar's tourism industry remained
undeveloped due to various reasons after the country regained
independence in 1948.
</P>
<P>
During the 40 years between 1948 and 1988, the number of
foreign tourists to the country was 30,000 annually, bringing the
country less than 10 million U.S. dollars of foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
After the Myanmar State Law and Order Restoration Council
(SLORC),  the present State Peace and Development Council (SPDC),
took over the state power in late 1988, it carried out a major
reform in its economic policy including that of tourism.
</P>
<P>
First it extended the period of stay for foreign visitors in
Myanmar from seven days to 14 days in May 1989. In 1993 the period
of tourist visa was further extended to 28 days. The moves were
aimed at giving foreign travelers sufficient time to stay in
Myanmar and thus helping the country earn more foreign exchange
from their spending.
</P>
<P>
In June 1990, Myanmar promulgated its first Tourism Law since
independence to govern and guarantee the tourism business.
</P>
<P>
A new Ministry of Hotels and Tourism was set up in September
1992 to oversee the tourism business, which used to be run by a
company of hotels and tourism under the Ministry of Trade. The
formation of the new ministry has strengthened the macroscopical
direction of tourism activities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government also encourages the local private
sector and foreign entrepreneurs to involve in the tourism
industry. Before 1988, tourism was monopolized by the state. After
that year, the government has allowed both local and foreign
private sectors to do business in tourism, which has helped create
more job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
By the end of April this year, licenses have been issued to 449
hotels, motels and inns, of which more than 20 hotels are run with
foreign investment from companies of Singapore, Thailand, Japan,
Malaysia and China's Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
There are now one foreign travel agency, 626 local and 15
local-foreign joint ventures operating in hotel and tourism in
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in the sector, with Singapore in the first
place, amounted to 1.1 billion dollars in 40 projects by the end
of June this year, compared with the country's total foreign
investment of more than 7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has also opened to tourists more new sites such as
Sittwe, Mrauk Oo, Kyaikhtiyo, Myitkyina, Pathein and Chaungtha
Beach.
</P>
<P>
Yangon as the capital is no longer the only gateway to Myanmar
and entry by land has been allowed through border points with
China such as Bhamo, Namkham, Muse, Kyuhkok, Kunlong, Mongla and
those with Thailand such as Tachilek, Phaya Thonzu, Myawaddy and
Kawthoung.
</P>
<P>
To improve the tourism environment, Myanmar has renovated the
Yangon International Airport and built two more international
airports -- the Hanthawaddy airport in Bago, 80 kilometers from
Yangon, and the Mandalay airport, 680 km from the capital.
</P>
<P>
As part of its endeavors to promote the tourism industry,
Myanmar has established more aviation links with capital cities of
other countries, especially in 1995 and 1996 before the country's
first tourist year campaign was launched.
</P>
<P>
In these two years, Myanmar was able to open air links with
Brunei, Bhutan, India, Japan, Laos, Malaysia and Pakistan in
addition to those with Bangladesh, China, Singapore and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's domestic private airlines have also extended their
flights to border towns of neighboring Thailand, and Thai charter
planes are allowed to land at Myanmar's tourist sites since 1993.
</P>
<P>
The country has built more hotels to bring the total hotel
number to 523 with 14,714 rooms, compared with 39 hotels with
1,240 rooms in 1988.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the above measures, more than 200,000 foreign
travelers visited Myanmar annually in the last few years by air,
while the number of visitors entering through border points
exceeded 300,000.
</P>
<P>
Although the number of international visitors and high-class
hotels has increased, Myanmar still lacks trained personnel in the
industry.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Tourism Board and Singapore Hotels and Tourism
Education Center have been helping Myanmar in training more than
1,100 local students under a tourism cooperation agreement between
the two countries, and have turned out 38 diploma holders in hotel
management for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar initiated accords on cooperation in tourism
with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations and Thailand in
January and July respectively.
</P>
<P>
To attract more tourists from major tourist supplying
countries, Myanmar launched travel shows in Singapore and Thailand
successively in August and September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
