<HEADLINE> French Pharmaceutical Company Walks Away from Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Fierce competition has forced
Russel-Uclaf, a French multinational pharmaceutical company, to
withdraw from the China dexamethasone market that it dominated for
two decades.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned Tianjin Pharmaceutical Corporation (TPC) in
Tianjin, north China's port city, broke into the European market
last year after 20 years of bitter competition with the French
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
"My company started to have a leading role in China in 1994,
and Russel-Uclaf lost millions of dollars in the price war that
occured afterward. Russel-Uclaf's attempt to regain its previous
market share also turned out be a Waterloo," said Shi Chunsheng,
president of the Tianjin company.
</P>
<P>
However, the Tianjin company, the largest Chinese producer of
dexamethasone, was kicked out of the game by Russel-Uclaf in 1982
and had to shut down its production lines.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, Tianjin Pharmaceutical Corporation resumed production
of the product, after having introduced advanced production lines
from abroad.
</P>
<P>
Now, TPC has more than a 90 percent share of China's
dexamethasone market, and five percent of the total Asian market,
said Shi Chunsheng, president of Tianjin Pharmaceutical
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Shi said that TPC's output value will reach one billion yuan
annually by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
