<HEADLINE> Hainan Starts New Round of Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Southernmost China's island
province of Hainan has unveiled a new round of moderate economic
growth, coming after bubbles in the local economy erupted in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Wang Xiaofeng, governor of Hainan, said that the province's
gross domestic product (GDP) reached 29.4 billion yuan in the
first nine months of this year, considerably above the country's
average.
</P>
<P>
This figure was also a 7.7 percent gain over the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
Hainan will be able to realize the goal of maintaining an 8
percent economic growth rate this year because the province's
industrial structure adjustment measures have taken effect, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Hainan's economy has ended a low-growth period that began
in the early 1990s when speculation in the local real estate
sector ran away from the island," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the province's economic growth rate reached a
record low, 4.3 percent, in 1995, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, investment in the local real estate industry resumed
growth in the past three quarters this year, and industrial
enterprises have seen profits as a whole after three successive
years of losses.
</P>
<P>
Investment in fixed assets also began to rise again, Wang said,
adding that the economy of Hainan has moved onto the right track
of healthy development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Rice Imports May be Cut by 50 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia will be able to halve
its huge rice imports next fiscal year, beginning on April 1999,
if rice production meets the target, the Jakarta Post Monday
quoted Minister of Agriculture Soleh Solahuddin as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We can reduce our imports by 50 percent if our rice (unhusked)
production could reach 52 million tons next fiscal year," the
minister said in South Sumatra provincial capital of Palembang on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The unhusked rice could be processed into 31 million metric
tons of milled rice. Indonesia's rice consumption is expected to
reach 32 million tons next year.
</P>
<P>
This year, domestic consumption is predicted at 31 million
tons, while the country's unhusked rice production could only
reach slightly over 46 million tons (28 million tons of milled
rice) due to the poor harvests.
</P>
<P>
To make up for the shortage, the government plans to import as
much as 4.1 million tons for the fiscal year ending in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
The central Bureau of Statistics in its latest report estimates
that the country's unhusked rice production this year will reach
46.44 million tons, slightly higher than its earlier prediction of
46.29 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The figure is still six percent lower than the 49.38 million
tons last year.
</P>
<P>
The State Logistics Agency earlier predicted that the country
would have to import at least 3.42 million tons of rice in
1999/2000 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Soleh said the government had conducted special efforts to
increase the size of the rice cultivation areas in a bid to boost
production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
