<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Telephone Installation Fee Drops in Hainan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Telecommunication authorities in
Hainan Province have decided to dramatically cut the fee charged for
opening up a telephone line.
</P>
<P>
As of November 1, urban telephone users will pay 1,000 yuan
(120.48 U.S. dollars) for their first telephone line, as compared
with the present 2,000 to 2,500 yuan. The cost to users in rural
townships and villages will drop from 1,500 to 600 yuan.
 The fee for setting up a mobile phone line will be cut from 1,500
to 1,000 yuan, but this price can fluctuate within a range of 20 to
30 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, telephone availability averaged 8.3 lines for every
100 person in the island province. The past five years have seen
an additional 130,000 mobile-phone users and 430,000 pager
users. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Launches Largest Banana Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Construction of the largest
banana plantation in Hainan, the island province of southernmost
China, was begun recently in the the city of Dongfang.
</P>
<P>
Undertaken with investment by a Hong Kong company, the project
involves some one billion yuan (120 million U.S. dollars) and will
be completed in three years.
</P>
<P>
According to plan, banana trees will be planted on 2,000 hectares
annually, and by 2001 the acreage is scheduled to reach 6,666
hectares producing 250,000 tons of bananas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
