<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeastern China Cracks Down On Electricity Theft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, November 2 (Xinhua) -- An official with a glass fibre
factory in the city of Benxi in northeastern China was recently
detained when he instructed electricians to steal electricity by
tapping into public power lines.
</P>
<P>
This was just one of the 9,796 cases of electricity theft
exposed during a major crackdown campaign launched recently by
electricity management in northeastern China where power theft
has cost the Northeastern Electricity Group (NEG), the regional
major power producer and supplier, over 300 million yuan (about
37.5 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
To reduce production costs, some enterprises resort to this
practice, and according to NEG officials, about half of companies
in the service industry such as restaurants, hotels, and ballrooms
are engaged in electricity embezzlement. Some simply plug into the
transformers.
</P>
<P>
NEG officials have allocated some 80 million yuan to reinforce
crackdown efforts and close loopholes. They have set up special
inspection units across the region, probing into major cases in
collaboration with the local police, and plan to install meters on
all transformers by the end of the year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
