<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jakarta Markets See Nervous Week, Says Analysts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Jakarta money and stock
markets expect thin trading with political concerns sidelining
players this week, the Indonesian Observer Monday quoted analysts
as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Players will adopt a wait-and-see attitude, watching the
political developments. They are worried that the condition will
heat up ahead of the MPR (People's Consultative Assembly) special
session," money market analyst Farial Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
The MPR will begin its special session on November 10 and
conclude it November 13. During the meeting a date will be set for
next year's general election.
</P>
<P>
"People won't sell their U.S. dollars because they think that
once the political tension worsens, the U.S. dollar will rise
again," Farial said.
</P>
<P>
A massive student demonstration last week sent the markets
reeling as investors took a back seat after cashing out. The
protesters asked President B.J. Habibie to immediately hand over
power to a transitional government and reiterated their rejection
of the MPR special session.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the possibility of larger student protests keeps
the sentiment weak on both the rupiah and the stocks.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody dares short selling on dollar. Although the rupiah does
have the potentials to strengthen, nobody has the guts to take a
short dollar position at this level because of political
uncertainties," Farial added.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah closed at 7,700/7,750 to the greenback on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jakarta stocks are expected to see a bearish week
with investors taking a back seat.
</P>
<P>
Dominant political factors will result in a market correction
this week, fund manager Ario Adhikari told the Indonesian
Observer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
