<HEADLINE> Sampras: A man with Mission into Paris Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Pete Sampras became the man with
a mission going into the Paris Open Indoor tennis tournament
which started off here today.
</P>
<P>
If he successfully defends his title, the current world number
one will move a step forward to his dream of ending the year in
the top spot for a record sixth consecutive time.
</P>
<P>
Last year, after clinching the Paris Open and the following
ATP Tour world championship title, Sampras tied the record set by
his fellow American Jimmy Connors through 1974-1978 of occupying
world number one spot for five years in a row.
</P>
<P>
Sampras had already lost chances to boost his computer points
by crashing out of the Eurocard Open semifinals last week. But to
his comfort, two major rivals Chilean Marcelo Rios and Australian
Patrick Rafter, currently second and third in the world
respectively, also failed to win.
</P>
<P>
The three-horse battle for the men's top ranking will continue
this week at the Paris Open and may only be decided at the
season-ending world championship starting on November 23 in
Hanover, Germany.
</P>
<P>
Sampras has a tricky start on his defending rout, with his
first round opponent Thomas Johansson of Sweden. He is drawn to
meet Rafter in the quarterfinals, and waiting for him in the
semifinals will be either Rios or Dutchman Richard Krajicek, who
ousted him at the Eurocard and preserves a career edge over him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Bans Re-selling of Vehicles Imported with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar Investment
Commission (MIC) has prohibited enterprises doing business in the
country from re-selling their motor vehicles imported with tax
relief or tax exemption.
</P>
<P>
A latest issue of the local Myanmar Business News, published by
the Union of Myanmar Chamber of Commerce and Industry, quoted a
directive of the MIC as warning that the motor vehicles in
question will be confiscated and entrepreneurs will be fined
unless the directive is followed.
</P>
<P>
The directive said that the enterprises are required to apply
to the MIC in case of re-sale of the vehicles and then pay the
prescribed customs duty and taxes as well as import of new ones.
</P>
<P>
The companies are to abide by the decision of the MIC passed
for individual cases for payment of duty and taxes, the directive
added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Myanmar authorities have also banned use of cars
imported under the transit trade system since September 1997,
saying that cars imported under the system could only be
transported across Myanmar to a third country.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, in 1997-98 fiscal year which
ended in March, the number of motor vehicles operating in Myanmar
totaled 243,853, of which 239,764 are privately-owned, 3,182
state-operated and 907 cooperatives-run. The motor vehicles
comprise passenger buses and haulage trucks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
