<HEADLINE> Ukraine Rejects Territory Claims by Russian Deputies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, November 1 (Xinhua) -- The Ukrainian Foreign Ministry
Sunday rejected territory claims by some Russian State Duma
(parliament) deputies, saying that the demands were not conducive
to mutual confidence and understanding of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In a statement the Foreign Ministry referred to claims made by
some Russian deputies over Ukraine's Crimea and Sevastopol when
the State Duma met on October 23 to review a Russian-Ukrainian
agreement on early warning systems for missile attacks and
space-monitoring system.
</P>
<P>
The statement complained that a number of deputies make the
same claims from time to time when the State Duma discusses
Russo-Ukrainian relations.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministry said it hoped the Russian executive branch
would make appropriate responses to the anti-Ukraine remarks.
</P>
<P>
It also expressed puzzlement and concern over the State Duma's
delay in ratifying the Treaty of Friendship, Cooperation and
Partnership signed by Russian President Boris Yeltsin and his
Ukrainian counterpart Leonid Kuchma on May 31, 1997. 
</P>
