<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Calls For More Patience </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie Sunday reminded the country of the need for patience and
direction as the country nears the special session of the People's
Consultative Assembly (MPR).
</P>
<P>
Addressing the national conference of the Indonesian Islamic
Propagation Council here, the president called on religious
leaders to understand and lend direction to what he called
"people's dynamism."
</P>
<P>
He said the country is facing several important political
events, including the special session of the MPR, the general
election in mid-1999 and the presidential election in late
December 1999.
</P>
<P>
In the run-up to these national events, the political
temperature normally tends to rise, national newspapers Monday
quoted the president as saying.
</P>
<P>
While Habibie and some 400 members of the council gathered at
the State Palace on Sunday, over 5,000 members of the Islamic
Supporters of the Constitution staged a pro-Habibie rally in
Central Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
The gathering followed a large anti-Habibie protest held last
Wednesday when 8,000 students demonstrated outside the Parliament
House, demanding the establishment of a transitional government.
The demonstrators also rejected the coming special session of the
MPR, the country's highest legislative body.
</P>
<P>
The MPR will begin its special session on November 10 and
conclude it November 13. During the meeting a date will be set for
next year's general election.
</P>
<P>
Various parties have been at odds over the need for the
session, with some demanding that it be canceled.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian political observers have warned that conflict among
political forces may lead to unrest during the upcoming special
session of the MPR.
</P>
<P>
"Collisions between various mass groups before the special
session could lead to bloodshed and the paralysis of all state
systems, unless the government take concrete steps to prevent it
happening," Merdeka daily Sunday quoted former home affairs
minister Rudini as saying.
</P>
<P>
Rudini suggested that the government establish a national
consensus involving leading figures from the political
establishment and the opposition as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Muslim scholar Nurcholish Madjid and politician Mochtar Buchori
raised the issue of possible unrest in a discussion held on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Nurcholish said the special session could be marked with unrest
if there were indications that the event was contrived only to
maintain Habibie's position in power.
</P>
<P>
Habibie, however, could avert the catastrophe with fair and
open play, and by keeping his promise to hold the general election
in May next year as scheduled, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mochtar said physical clashes could take place given that many
parties have already begun to trade threats.
</P>
<P>
He said Indonesians must learn how to establish a civil society
in peaceful ways. "We are still learning. So I would not be
surprised if there was unrest because of the many interests
involved," he added.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Minister of Security and Defense and Armed Forces
Commander Gen. Wiranto said that the Armed Forces is ready to
safeguard the special session from any effort to disrupt the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Regarding demonstrations, he said recent rallies staged by
various parties were actually shows of force which could lead to
anarchy.
</P>
<P>
"It is not forbidden to stage protests, but they must abide by
the regulations," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
