<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmer Detained for Illegal Tree Felling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The forestry police in the city
of Mianyang in southwest China's Sichuan Province have detained a
farmer suspected of illegal tree felling.
</P>
<P>
The forestry police said that Zhong Dailin has been detained
for illegally cutting down 71 trees which protect the Yangtze
River and running a lumber processing factory for large profits.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan is located at the upper reach of the Yangtze and
the forests there play an important role in preventing
soil erosion, one of the factors responsible for the heavy
flooding on the river this past summer.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan possesses one of China's three largest forest areas.
</P>
<P>
The police said his actions violate the regulations adopted by
the State Council.
</P>
<P>
They are now investigating the case, and if the alleged facts
prove true, Zhong will be punished under the law.
</P>
<P>
The province imposed a tree-felling ban in its primitive
forests on September 1, and the Provincial People's Congress
adopted a law to punish offenders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
