<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Riot Team to Announce Findings Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian
government-sponsored fact-finding team investigating the country's
May riots is scheduled to submit its executive report to the
government on Tuesday, the Indonesian Observer Monday quoted the
team leader as saying.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with the paper on Sunday, the Joint
Fact-Finding Team leader Marzuki Darusman said the team will "most
likely" deliver their executive report to the government at the
Ministry of Justice.
</P>
<P>
The team was formed on July 23 under a joint decree by the
Defense and Security Ministry, Justice Ministry, Attorney
General's Office, and the ministries of women affairs, home
affairs and foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
"Five officials have confirmed they will attend the meeting...
with the exception of (Home Affairs Minister) Syarwan Hamid who
will not be present due to an out of town official trip," Marzuki
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the team has never received an opportunity "as big as
this one" for an official meeting with the government's
representatives.
</P>
<P>
Mandated to report to the government on October 23, the team
has been twice delayed in the announcement of their findings due
to a conflict in the schedule for a final meeting between the six
government representatives.
</P>
<P>
Marzuki has dismissed reports of an internal rift between
members of the team, saying that the postponement "was not a
result of a split within the team."
</P>
<P>
"The delays have taken place due to the team's (difference of
opinions) in the 'designing' of the report's final draft," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The 18-member team was entrusted with the task of investigating
and, if possible, unveiling the instigators and perpetrators of
the May riots, which some say were organized.
</P>
<P>
The team is also investigating claims made by human rights
groups that there were rampant sexual assaults and rapes during
the riots which killed 1,200 people and led to the downfall of
former president Soeharto. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
