<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Finishes 1-2 in NYC Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenya swept the top two
spots in the New York City Marathon on Sunday with John Kagwe
edging Joseph Chebet in the final strides with a time of two
hours eight minutes and 45 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Kagwe, the hot pre-race favorite, geared up to beat his rival
to defend his title in the second-closest finish in the race's
29-year history.
</P>
<P>
Chebet finished only three seconds in Kagwe's wake, repeating
the same rankings last year. Zebedayo Bayo of Tanzania placed
third in 2:08.51.
</P>
<P>
The early part of the race was paced slowly, but the second
half saw 1996 Olympic champion Josie Thugwane of South Africa and
1997 world champion Abel Anton of Spain lead the field.
</P>
<P>
But with 22 kilometers to go, five runners from Kenya
controled the race. In the final stage, Kagwe, Chebet and Bayo
dropped the other runners for good, and had a tough battle among
themselves.
</P>
<P>
Kagwe and Fiacconi each collected 50,000 U.S. dollars for the
first prize.
</P>
<P>
In the women's event, Franca Fiacconi of Italy took the title
by beating twice champion Tegla Loroupe of Kenya in 2:25.17.
Adriana Fernandez of Mexico finished second in 2:26.33 ahead of
the ailing Loroupe, 2:30.26. 
</P>
</TEXT>
