<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gascoigne Booked on Return after Rehab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Paul Gascoigne, ending his life
in a rehabilitation clinic, had a yellow card in Middlesbrough's
1-1 draw with Nottingham Forest in an English Premier League
match on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Less than a month after he started treatment for stress,
alcohol problems and depression at the clinic, the England
midfielder returned to action as his team were shocked by a
dramatic late Forest equaliser.
</P>
<P>
Middlesbrough seemed to be heading towards three points when
Gascoigne was substituted in the 78th minute. But an 89th minute
goal from Forest teenager Marlon Harewood cancelled out the home
side's 22nd minute goal by Brian Deane.
</P>
<P>
Gascoigne looked delighted to be back, smiling and joking with
some of Forest's players in the tunnel before running out on to
the pitch. He played a largely reserved first half, showing just
a few touches of his passing skills.
</P>
<P>
But the midfielder, who spent 16 days in the clinic in
mid-October and will continue to be treated, was booked early in
the second half for a poor tackle on Scot Gemmill, before being
substituted.
</P>
<P>
After dominating the first half, Middlesbrough, promoted to
the top flight last season, seemed to lose direction in the
second half against Forest, 18th in the 20-team league.
</P>
<P>
Deane, who joined Middlesbrough from Benfica last month, took
his goal well, firing the ball into the right-hand corner from
close range after a superb long pass from Andy Townsend, who
upstaged Gascoigne in midfield.
</P>
<P>
But Harewood turned well in the area to fire in a vital
equaliser and went close to scoring a dramatic winner in the
dying seconds.
</P>
<P>
Despite the draw, Middlesbrough moved up to fourth with 17
points from their first 11 games, three points behind
third-placed Arsenal and five points behind leaders Aston Villa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0241 </DOCNO>
