<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's First Global Satellite Telephone, Paging Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, November 1 (Xinhua) -- A Bermuda-based U.S.
company announced Sunday that its hand-held, global satellite
phone and paging system, the world's first, is now commercially
available to customers.
</P>
<P>
Iridium World Communications said in a statement that it offers
satellite voice, cellular roaming and calling card and other
services 24 hours a day and seven days a week by using its
constellation of 66 low earth orbit satellites. Phones are being
produced and shipped to the regional Iridium Gateways by Motorola
of the U.S. and Kyocera of Japan. Global page service will
commence in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
Whether their phone is in satellite or cellular mode, the
company said, an Iridium customer will be reachable at a single
phone number, anywhere they happen to be. If their phone is turned
off, they can be contacted on their Iridium pager.
</P>
<P>
Iridium satellite service is authorized in more than 120
countries and regions, with 200 markets expected by year-end, the
company said. More than 270 distribution agreements have been
negotiated worldwide, with service providers and roaming partners,
which provide Iridium access to over 105 million wireless
telephone customers in 125 countries.
</P>
<P>
Customers can select the communication options among services
including satellite, cellular, paging and landline.
</P>
<P>
A direct satellite link to a handheld satellite phone provides
incoming and outgoing communications in remote areas, poorly
covered regions and other locations where terrestrial networks are
not available.
</P>
<P>
Its roaming service allows customers to roam across previously
incompatible terrestial wireless networks, enabling them to keep
one telephone number and receive one telephone bill for calls made
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
Iridium pager service will provide global alphanumeric
messaging to belt-worn pagers. When combined with the voice mail
option, callers can reach the customers worldwide, including on
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Its calling card enables customers to make phone calls from
public and private wireline and wireless phones in 58 countries.
</P>
<P>
The company said that it had worked for 11 years before being
operational. "Iridium will open up the world of business,
commerce, disaster relief and humanitarian assistance" with its
service, the company said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
