<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Tongan Prince </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin met with
Prince 'Ulukalala-Lavaka-Ata, Tonga's minister of foreign affairs
and defence, in the Chinese capital on October 26.
</P>
<P>
Jiang expressed his welcome to the prince on his visit to China
right after he was appointed Tonga's minister of foreign affairs
and defence and on signing the joint communique on the
establishment of diplomatic ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president expressed appreciation for the farsighted
strategic vision and political savvy King Taufa'ahau Tupou IV
exhibited by deciding to establish ties with China.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the move was a logical historic development and the
inevitable result of the development of traditional friendship and
good relations between the people of the two nations, hence laying
a foundation for the further growth of the ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese government is prepared to join the Tongan
government to bring into the 21st century the Sino-Tongan
relations characterized by a long-term stability, sincere
friendship and all-round cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Prince 'Ulukalala-Lavaka-Ata said that it was a great honor for
him to meet with President Jiang and conveyed King Taufa'ahau
Tupou IV's warm greetings and cordial regards to the Chinese
leader, the Chinese government and people.
</P>
<P>
He said Tonga values the development of its friendship and
relations of cooperation with China. He noted that with their
joint efforts, the two countries have signed the joint communique
on the establishment of diplomatic ties between the two nations,
thus normalizing their relations.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that this has opened broad prospects for
the two sides to further their friendship and mutually beneficial
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The prince said that the Tongan government will abide by the
principles outlined in the joint communique and will steadfastly
refrain form any official relation in any form with Taiwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
