<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice Premier Meets Tongan Prince </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier Qian
Qichen met with Prince 'Ulukalala-Lavaka-Ata, Tonga's minister of
foreign and defence, and his party in the Chinese capital on
October 26.
</P>
<P>
Qian congratulated the prince on his appointment of Tonga's
minister of foreign affairs and defence.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice-premier extended his welcome to the prince on
his visit to China and on signing the joint communique on the
establishment of diplomatic ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy to see the rapid development of the Sino-Tongan
relations in recent years and the constant deepening of the
mutual understanding," Qian said, adding that particularly, King
Taufa'ahau Tupou IV made the decision to normalize Tonga's
relations with China since his unofficial visit to China in July
of last year.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that now, China and Tonga have established diplomatic
ties, thus opening a new chapter in the relations between the two
countries. And he added that "it is the inevitable result of the
development of the international situation, deserving our
celebrations."
</P>
<P>
Prince 'Ulukalala-Lavaka-Ata said he is honored to have had the
opportunity to visit China at this historic moment and to sign the
joint communique on establishment of the diplomatic ties between
the two nations on behalf of King Taufa'ahau Tupou IV.
</P>
<P>
He said China is a great nation and Tonga can learn a lot from
it.
</P>
<P>
He said Tonga understands and supports China's principle stand
on the Taiwan issue, and holds that the Taiwan issue is China's
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Tonga will refrain from any official exchanges
with Taiwan following the establishment of its diplomatic ties
with China. 
</P>
