<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton says All Options Open to Deal with Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Sunday said Iraq's decision to suspend cooperation with U.N. arms
inspectors violated its commitments to the United Nations and all
options remained open for dealing with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also said he was pleased that the U.S. Security Council
had strongly condemned Iraq's action. He made the remarks in an
interview with the American Urban Radio network.
</P>
<P>
"It's a clear violation of the commitments that he (Iraq
President Saddam Hussein) made, a clear violation of the U.N.
Security Council resolutions," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"I personally am very pleased that the U.N. Security Council,
including some people that I think have been a little tolerant
with him in the past, strongly condemned what he did," the
president said.
</P>
<P>
"From my point of view, we should keep all our options open,
examine the nature of the action and where we are, and then do
what's best for the integrity of the United Nations and the
interest, the security interests of the people of the United
States," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he had received a couple of briefings on the
issue, and that his national security team was meeting late on
Sunday afternoon for further discussions.
</P>
<P>
Also on Sunday, U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen returned
to Washington after cutting short an Asian tour.
</P>
<P>
"I think everybody is getting weary of dealing with (Iraqi
President) Saddam Hussein," Cohen told reporters at Andrews Air
Force Base.
</P>
<P>
He said Washington would prefer any action against Iraq to be
taken in concert with the United Nations and allies, but a
unilateral U.S. attack "has always been an option that we could
pursue."
</P>
<P>
"He (Saddam) continues to flout the rules. He continues to
break agreement after agreement, and I think that we are concerned
about this," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Iraq announced that it was suspending cooperation
with U.N. arms inspectors and monitors until the Security Council
reviewed the lifting of sanctions and purged its teams of what
Baghdad terms "American spies and agents."
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Barry Toiv said Cohen, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, National Security Adviser Sandy Berger and
other top security officials would meet Sunday afternoon to
discuss the latest crisis with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"They'll be reviewing the situation and consider possible
courses of action," Toiv said. The spokesman said Clinton may meet
with the national security team as early as Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
