<DOCNO> XIE19981102.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Establishes Diplomatic Ties with Tonga </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 2 (Xinhua) - The People's Republic of China
and the Kingdom of Tonga today formally announced the
establishment of diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan and
Prince 'Ulukalala-Lavaka-Ata, Tonga's minister of foreign affairs
and defense, signed a joint communique in this respect on behalf
of their respective governments in Beijing on October 26.
</P>
<P>
The two countries agreed to recognize each other and establish
diplomatic ties at the ambassadorial level.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government acknowledged the national independence,
sovereignty and territorial integrity of the Kingdom of Tonga and
voiced support for the nation's efforts for economic
development. The Tongan government recognized that there is only
one China and the government of the People's Republic of China is
the sole legitimate government representing the whole
of China. Tonga agreed that Taiwan is an inalienable part of the
Chinese territory.
</P>
<P>
The two governments agreed to offer all necessary assistance
for the establishment and operations of each other's embassies on
a reciprocal basis and in accordance with relevant regulations and
international practices.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao welcomed the
establishment of diplomatic ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said today that China and Tonga are developing countries
which share many similarities.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said normalizing relations is in the fundamental interests
of people in both nation, and is conducive to peace and
development in the Asia-Pacific Region. He also pointed to the
broad prospects for the mutually beneficial cooperation in all
areas.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that on the basis of the five
principles of peaceful coexistence, friendly and cooperative
relations between the two countries will develop steadily in the
future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
