<HEADLINE> Tanjug Reporters Sentenced by Ethnic Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRISTINA, Yugoslavia November 1 (Xinhua) -- Two Yugoslav
journalists have been sentenced to 60-day imprisonment by a
martial court of the ethnic Albanian rebels, a Serbian official
said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Radovan Urosevic, Director of the Pristina Media Center, told
Xinhua that the two reporters for Tanjug, the Yugoslav news agency
was sentenced on Saturday by the court of Kosovo Liberation Army
for disobeying KLA order while driving in its controlled area.
</P>
<P>
Tanjug said that its journalists disappeared on October 16 when
they were covering the Kosovo Crisis.
</P>
<P>
Urosevic said that by sentencing the two journalists, KLA
wanted to show to the world that it was a major factor in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"It is unbelievable that the Western countries have turned a
blind eye to such illegal act", which constituted a breach of the
agreement on Kosovo reached by Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and U.S. Special Envoy Richard Holbrooke, he said.
</P>
