<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turnout Considered Key in Close Races in Tuesday Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 1 (Xinhua) -- Voter turnout, traditionally
low in midterm elections, could have significant impact on the
results of those close races in the November 3 midterm elections
in the United States, lawmakers said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Higher turnout is usually seen as helping Democrats, although
Republicans predicted their final-week campaign commercials,
including spots linking Democrats to the Clinton-Lewinsky matter,
would help attract more voters sympathetic to Republican
candidates.
</P>
<P>
"Our Republicans are energized," said Representative John
Linder, head of the House Republican campaign effort.
</P>
<P>
Both sides said turnout would be crucial in close races.
Representative Martin Frost, Linder's Democratic counterpart, said
many House districts will be decided by 1,000 or 2,000 votes.
"We're working turnout very hard. They are working turnout very
hard," he said on ABC's "This Week with Sam Donaldson and Cokie
Roberts."
</P>
<P>
House Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt said the 1996 House
elections came down to about 10,000 voters around the country and
"if people will get out and vote, then we will have a great
outcome on Tuesday."
</P>
<P>
But Republican Representative John Kasich, on NBC's "Meet the
Press" with Gephardt, predicted that the Republican would pick up
eight to 12 seats in the House.
</P>
<P>
Republicans now maintain a 228-206 advantage in the House, with
one Democratic-leaning independent. Republicans lead in the Senate
55-45.
</P>
<P>
Senator Bob Kerrey, a Democrat, who is leading the Senate
campaign drive, said on CBS' "Face the Nation" that voter turnout
will be critical in determining whether Democrats can keep
Republicans from gaining the 60 seats needed to nullify the
minority party weapon of blocking legislation through filibusters.
</P>
<P>
Curtis Gans, director of the non-partisan Committee for the
Study of the American Electorate, said he expected a typical
midterm turnout of between 36 percent and 38 percent of eligible
voters, although voter reaction to the Monica Lewinsky affair
could have an unpredictable effect.
</P>
<P>
While voter registration is up, Gans said, voter interest is
down, with a record low 17.5 percent of eligible voters
participating in statewide primaries this year.
</P>
<P>
Civil rights leader Jesse Jackson, on CNN's "Late Edition,"
predicted that the Democrats' "basic coalition of
African-Americans, labor, Hispanics and women, that core
coalition, is going to vote in big numbers."
</P>
<P>
But on the other side, Christian Coalition Executive Director
Randy Tate foresaw a big turnout from religious conservatives. He
said conservatives, with help from 36 million election guides the
Christian Coalition sent out Sunday, "could be the deciding vote
in probably two dozen House races, and a half-dozen Senate races."
</P>
<P>
Senate Republican Campaign Committee chairman Senator Mitch
McConnell told CBS that both sides "are doing everything they can
to motivate their own people." But, he added, "frankly, we don't
know what's going to happen. We'll find out Tuesday night."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
